<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, June 16, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Los Alamos Nuclear Secrets Found
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two computer hard drives containing nuclear secrets from
the Los Alamos weapons lab have been found behind a copying machine within the
lab's top-secret secure area and are being evaluated, the Energy Department and
government sources said Friday. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson said the two
hard drives, believed to be the ones that disappeared more than six weeks ago,
were in an area that apparently had been searched before. Richardson said
investigators are looking into ''inconsistencies'' surrounding the whereabouts
of the devices. The FBI has examined the drives for fingerprints and they were
to be examined electronically on Saturday, said an official who spoke on
condition of not being identified further.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Senate Validates E-Signatures
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton will soon usher in a new stage in the
digital age where the electronic signature and Internet-conveyed record have the
same legal standing as a pen-and-paper document. The president has strongly
backed the electronic signature legislation that cleared the Senate Friday by an
87-0 vote, saying it will marry the old value of consumer protection with the
newest technologies. The bill, which the House passed earlier in the week by
426-4, sets a national framework for giving online signatures legal status.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Koreas End Propaganda Broadcasts
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Name-calling on the world's most heavily armed
border was replaced Friday with pop songs and words of reconciliation, as North
and South Korea stopped propaganda broadcasts across the Demilitarized Zone.
Koreas' leaders pledged to work together to end half a century of hostilities
and unite families separated by the Korean War. During the three-day summit,
which ended Thursday, North Korean leader Kim Jong Il ordered his
state-controlled media and military to stop all anti-South propaganda. South
Korea reciprocated Friday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.N. Verifies Israeli Withdrawal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- In a setback for U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
Lebanon on Friday rejected the United Nations' verification of Israel's
withdrawal from south Lebanon, saying Israel still controls some Lebanese
territory. Annan had said earlier Friday at U.N. headquarters that the United
Nations has confirmed the Israeli withdrawal is complete. That announcement is
supposed to clear the way for U.N. troops to move into the border area and help
Lebanese forces restore peace and regain authority in the region.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Calif. Votes For Cleaner Vehicles
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DIAMOND BAR, Calif. (AP) -- Southern California's air-quality agency voted
Friday to require nearly 11,000 transit buses and garbage trucks to convert to
cleaner-burning alternative fuels, setting what environmentalists hope will be
an example for the rest of the country. The rules are believed to be the first
of their kind in the nation. The rules, approved unanimously by the South Coast
Air Quality Management District, require that all new vehicles bought by transit
agencies and trash companies run on natural gas, methanol, electricity or fuel
cells.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Warmest Spring on Record for U.S.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- According to the National Climatic Data Center, Spring
2000 was the hottest on record for the United States. The agency said that
meteorological spring -- March through May -- averaged 55.5 degrees Fahrenheit
over the United States. That's 0.4 degrees warmer than the previous record, set
in 1910.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bell Atlantic-GTE Deal OK'd
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators gave their blessing today to the merger
of Bell Atlantic and GTE Corp., a union that transforms one of the offsprings of
the old Bell system into the nation's largest local phone company and wireless
provider. It allows the firms to launch a combined business under the new name
Verizon Communications.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 266; Nasdaq Gains 15
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks fell steeply today after Xerox and a
regional banking company issued profit warnings. In its biggest selloff in two
months, the Dow Jones industrial average plunged 265.52 points to close at
10,449.30. On the NYSE, losers led gainers 1,584-1,307. The Nasdaq was up 14.82
at 3,860.56.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pacers Defeat Lakers 120-87
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Led by Jalen Rose, the Indiana Pacers put on a fantastic
shooting display that kept the Lakers' championship plans on hold. Starting
6-for-6 on 3-pointers and shooting 75 percent in the first quarter, Indiana
manhandled Los Angeles 120-87 Friday night in Game 5 of the NBA Finals. A
four-point play by Miller turned a five-point lead into a nine-point lead just
seven minutes in, and three 3-pointers by Rose helped the Pacers score 39 points
in the first quarter -- their best of the postseason.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
