<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 22 Low Caste India Villagers Killed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Gunmen dressed in black stormed a
village in eastern India and shot dead 22 members of a low caste
community, domestic news agencies reported.
</P>
<P>
   The attackers were members of the Ranvir Sena, a private militia
run by upper caste feudal landlords, K.A. Jacob, the police chief
in eastern Bihar state said, quoted by the Press Trust of India.
</P>
<P>
   The massacre was apparently in retaliation for the killing of 12
upper caste villagers last week.
</P>
<P>
   The attackers stormed several homes in Miapur village late
Friday and sprayed bullets into the sleeping victims, all members
of the Yadav community of cattle herders. Twenty-two people died
immediately while an unspecified number were seriously wounded.
</P>
<P>
   However, some villagers put the number of dead at 24, PTI said.
</P>
<P>
   The last major strike by the Ranvir Sena was in Narayanpur
village in the neighboring district of Jehanabad, infamous for its
caste wars.
</P>
<P>
   Caste strife is endemic in Bihar, one of India's most lawless
and backward states. The Ranvir Sena is locked in a war of
attrition with ultra-left organizations like the Maoist Communist
Center and the People's War Group who say they represent the
interest of lower caste peasants.
</P>
<P>
   About 83 percent of India's one billion people are believers of
Hinduism, which classifies its people into a social hierarchy of
castes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
