<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 00:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pacers Send Series Back to L.A.  </HEADLINE>
By STEVE HERMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Thanks to Jalen Rose, Reggie Miller and some
incredible shooting, the Indiana Pacers extended Larry Bird's
coaching career at least one more game.
</P>
<P>
   Bird, who took Indiana to the Eastern Conference finals twice
and then to the championship series for the first time in franchise
history, said all along he would not coach another season. A loss
Friday night would have ended his coaching career.
</P>
<P>
   But with 32 points from Rose and 25 from Miller, the Pacers
routed the Los Angeles Lakers 120-87 to pull within 3-2 in the
best-of-seven series. Game 6 is Monday in Los Angeles. A seventh
game, if necessary, would also be in L.A. on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''After the last game, I talked about not letting them celebrate
on our court,'' Rose said. ''I was serious about that. This is the
first time the Pacers have been to the NBA Finals. It can be old
hat to the Lakers, but for this to be happening in our town, we
didn't want the fans to leave feeling the season is a
disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   He needn't have worried.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers, who blew a 10-point lead before losing 120-118 in
overtime in Game 4 Wednesday night, dominated Game 5 from the
start. This time, there was no collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ''They didn't play well and we played extremely well,'' Bird
said. ''It's up to us to keep the pressure on and go out there and
win a game. But I still think they feel very good about themselves,
up 3-2 and two games at home.
</P>
<P>
   ''The game the other night, we fought so hard and play so well
but let it slip away. It was great to see the guys come back and
play so well tonight,'' Bird said. ''The only time we got in
trouble was when we missed assignments, didn't rotate. Overall, we
played as well as we can play. But they still have the upper hand,
and they know that.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana led 64-45 at the half, 86-67 after three quarters and
took its biggest lead at 33 points, several times in the closing
minutes, long after Bird had replaced all the starters except Rose.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was very determined,'' Rose said. ''Obviously, you're
disappointed when you don't play the way you're capable of playing.
And anytime you're down 1-3 you have to come out and show your
game. You can't leave anything in the tank or your season's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose was 12-of-18 from the field, including 4-of-5 3-pointers,
and all four of his free throw attempts. Miller was 7-for-12,
including 4-of-6 3-pointers and all seven of his shots from the
foul line.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got to have scoring out of both of them,'' Bird said.
''Jalen's a playmaker and when he gets it going, they forget about
Reggie sometimes and he'll pop it from the side. Together, when
they get it going like tonight, they're fun to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal, who had 35 points, was the only consistent
scorer for the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We realize that's the key,'' Mark Jackson said. ''It's tough
to do because when you're doubling on Shaq you're giving up
something on somebody else.
</P>
<P>
   ''But we had to make a statement from the beginning that we're
not here to roll over. We look forward to going back to California,
because our objective is to win this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The only Lakers rally came late in the third quarter, when they
cut the lead to 15.
</P>
<P>
   A basket and two free throws by Rose pushed the lead back to 19.
Then, after two baskets by O'Neal, Austin Croshere hit two free
throws on a flagrant foul by Rick Fox. The Pacers kept the ball,
and eight seconds later Kobe Bryant picked up his fifth foul and
Mark Jackson hit two free throws to give Indiana an 84-65 lead. Los
Angeles never came closer than 17 points after that.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers shot 57.4 percent for the game. Indiana also had 10
3-pointers, including four by Rose and three by Miller in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' only lead was after Glen Rice hit one of two free
throws at the start of the game to make it 1-0. Rice finished with
11 points.
</P>
<P>
   A basket by Miller, a rebound basket by Rik Smits and the first
3-pointer by Miller gave the Pacers a 7-1 lead before the first Los
Angeles basket, a 3-pointer by Ron Harper. Los Angeles tied the
game at 9. But two free throws by Smits and the first 3-pointer by
Rose started another big Indiana run, and the Lakers never
recovered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
