<HEADLINE> Notes From Friday's Baseball Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Indians-Tigers:
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: OF Manny Ramirez was scheduled to begin a rehab
assignment Friday at Double-A Akron. The Indians hope Ramirez, on
the DL since May 29 with a strained left hamstring, can rejoin them
by the middle of next week. ... 3B Travis Fryman said he still
believes the Chicago White Sox think the Indians are the team to
beat in the AL Central. ''The more they play well against us,
though, the more its going to go towards easing that thought from
their minds,'' Fryman said.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: The Tigers are 13-7 in games where 3B Dean Palmer has
at least one RBI. ... Juan Encarnacion hit just .130 (6-for-46) in
his first 12 games after missing 10 games due to injury and a
suspension. ... Friday's game was the first of several planned for
radio cast to OF Juan Gonzalez's native Puerto Rico. Gonzalez's
friend and Tigers Latin America liaison Luis Mayoral handled the
play-by-play.
White Sox-Yankees:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: The White Sox entered the day with a 5&AMP;frac12;-game lead over
Cleveland. At this point last season, the White Sox trailed the
Indians by 12 games. ... Chicago's eight-game road winning streak
is the team's longest since winning eight straight July 11-Aug. 1,
1993. ... Starter James Baldwin was 17-3 with a 3.06 ERA since Aug.
1.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: 2B Chuck Knoblauch was back in the lineup, leading off
and playing second base one night after being sent home in the
sixth inning. Knoblauch made a career-high three errors on
Thursday. ... Chris Turner started at catcher, while Jorge Posada
played designated hitter. Manager Joe Torre wanted to try Turner
with struggling David Cone, who had one win in his first 12 starts.
Turner caught Cone on May 20 in Cleveland when Cone allowed two
runs in 6 1-3 innings and got a no-decision. ... Rookie Jake
Westbrook will be called up from Triple-A Columbus to start
Saturday. ''He seems polished. He has basic stuff and is very
mature,'' Torre said.
Blue Jays-Red Sox:
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: The Blue Jays got some luck in the first inning when
RHP Kelvim Escobar struggled. With runners on first and second and
five runs already in, Scott Hatteberg popped out to Raul Mondesi in
right field for the second out. Troy O'Leary tagged from second and
the throw got by 3B Tony Batista, who then kicked it into the Blue
Jays dugout, allowing O'Leary to score and Wilton Veras to advance
to third. But Toronto appealed, and the umpires ruled O'Leary left
second too early. That erased a run, an error, and ended the
inning. ... Mondesi's first-inning home run on Friday night helped
Toronto set a club record with homers in 15 consecutive games. It
was Mondesi's 13th of the year.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: Jeff Frye has hit safely in 10 consecutive games, and 22
of the last 23. ... Brian Daubach had just nine hits in his last 56
at-bats before homering in the first inning. ... The back-to-back
homers by Carl Everett and Daubach were Boston's fifth consecutive
homers of the year.
Rangers-Devil Rays:
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: Thursday night's game at Baltimore didn't end until
nearly 1 a.m. after a rain delay of 2 hours, 7 minutes. The team
didn't arrive at its hotel in St. Petersburg, Fla., until 5:30 a.m.
... RHP Jared Camp was claimed off waivers from Cleveland and
optioned to Double-A Tulsa. OF Ruben Mateo (broken leg) was moved
from the 15-day to the 60-day DL to make room on the roster. ...
LHP Matt Perisho (1-0) was scheduled to make his first start of the
season Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: RHP Juan Guzman was moved to the 60-day DL after a
setback in a minor league rehab start for Triple-A Durham. He left
Thursday night's outing with shoulder stiffness after throwing 45
pitches in 3 2-3 innings. ... LF Greg Vaughn sat out his second
straight game since aggravating a right hamstring injury. CF Gerald
Williams also remained out of the starting lineup with a left hip
flexor strain. ... First-round draft pick Rocco Baldelli, a high
school outfielder from Cumberland, R.I., and fifth-round selection
Jace Brewer, a shortstop from Baylor, agreed to contracts.
Angels-Orioles:
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: The Angels had 44 steals in their first 65 games. They
didn't get 44 last year until their 114th game. ... RHP Tim Belcher
will make his first start and appearance of the season on Saturday.
He's returning from offseason surgery on his right arm. ... Rookie
C Bengie Molina made his 50th start of the season. He had 24 RBIs
in his previous 30 games.
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: The Orioles planned to active RHP Calvin Maduro
(elbow injury) off the DL Friday but decided to give him one more
rehabilitation assignment. He will pitch for Class A Frederick on
Saturday. ... LHP Chuck McElroy has allowed only one earned run in
his last 11 2-3 innings. After pitching two innings both Wednesday
and Thursday, he was to be given the night off Friday. ...
Washington Capitals Olie Kolzig, winner of the coveted Vezina
Trophy as the NHL's top goaltender, will throw out the ceremonial
first pitch Saturday night before the Orioles host Anaheim.
Athletics-Royals:
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: Former-Royal Kevin Appier was scheduled to make his
first start against his former team on Saturday. Appier is the
Royals' career leader in strikeouts (1,451) and ranks fourth in
wins (114), starts (269) and innings pitched (1,821). He was traded
to the A's for Jeff D'Amico, Brad Rigby and Blake Stein last July
31. ... The A's entered the three-game series with an 8-1-2 record
in road series this season. They won just seven series all of 1999.
... The A's began the game with the best road record in the major
leagues (21-12). The Royals tied for the best home record in the
American League (20-10).
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: The Royals will see six former teammates on the
A's: Sal Fasano, Jeremy Giambi, Kevin Appier, Mike Magnante, Rich
Sauveur and Scott Service have played for the Royals. Five Royals
(Jeff D'Amico, Brett Laxton, Dave McCarty, Blake Stein--DL and Jay
Witasick) are former A's. ... 2B Carlos Febles will head to
extended spring training Sunday to begin his rehabilitation for a
strained left shoulder. Febles has been on the 15-day DL since June
5. ... LHP Jose Rosado returned home Friday after going to
California to get a second opinion on his ailing left shoulder. He
has been on the DL since May 1 with tendinitis in his left
shoulder.
Mariners-Twins:
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: The Mariners' 35-28 start was their best ever through
63 games. Their previous best was 34-29 in 1997, '96 and '91. ...
Rob Ramsey's first major league victory on Thursday night marked
the first time in 24 games that a Mariners reliever got the win.
Since May 19, when Jose Mesa picked up the win against Tampa Bay,
Seattle starters had been 12-4 and the bullpen had been 0-7.
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: The Twins signed their top pick, RHP Adam Johnson,
the second overall pick in the draft earlier this month. Johnson
didn't work out for the Twins because the club feared the
aggressive pitcher from Cal State Fullerton might hurt himself
trying to impress them. Instead, he'll report to rookie ball in
Fort Myers, Fla. Johnson, 20, set a school record with 365
strikeouts in three seasons. ... The Twins decided to boost their
number of giveaway bobblehead Tony Oliva and Kirby Puckett dolls
later this summer from 5,000 to 10,000. Some fans were upset when
they waited in line for five hours for a Harmon Killebrew doll but
came away empty-handed.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Expos-Cubs:
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: Reliever Ugueth Urbina, who has been on the DL since
May 9 because of inflammation in his right elbow, joined the team
Friday and will throw on the side Sunday. He has been rehabbing in
Jupiter, Fla. ... Vladimir Guerrero is ahead of last year's home
run pace. He hit his 20th home run Friday. Last season, he did not
hit his 20th until July 21. The Expos are 13-4 when he homers. ...
White has hit safely in 16 of 19 games, and is batting .329
(25-for-76) in that stretch with six doubles and three home runs.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: Luis Montanez, the Cubs' first round pick in the June
draft, was in Chicago Friday to meet the team and will take batting
practice this weekend. Montanez, 18, was an all-state selection at
shortstop out of Coral Park High School in Miami. ... Kerry Wood
received a ''Big Mouth Billy Bass'' for his 23rd birthday. The fish
plaque sings ''Don't Worry Be Happy'' and ''Take Me to the River.''
... SS Jose Nieves, who is on an injury rehab assignment as he
recovers from a strained hamstring, joined Class AA West Tenn
Friday.
Marlins-Pirates:
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: Jim Leyland, who previously managed both clubs,
attended Friday night's Marlins-Pirates game. Leyland lives in
Pittsburgh and scouts for St. Louis. ... The Marlins are playing
their second series in Pittsburgh in less than three weeks, but
don't play the Pirates again this season after this weekend. ...
RHP Josh Beckett and C Ramon Castro will represent the Marlins in
the Future All-Star game July 9 in Atlanta. It is the second
successive season the Marlins have had two prospects chosen.
Pitchers Brad Penny and Jason Grilli were picked last season. ...
Luis Castillo stole his 27th base of the season in the second
inning Friday night, leaving him three short of breaking the
Marlins' record (Chuck Carr, 115 steals).
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: Pirates pitching prospect Sam McConnell is 7-1 at
Double-A Altoona with a 1.17 ERA that is the lowest among starting
pitchers in organized baseball. The 25-year-old left-hander
finished 1-7 at Altoona last season after going a combined 15-8 in
parts of two seasons at Single-A Lynchburg. ... Todd Ritchie, who
pitches Saturday, is 2-0 with a 2.08 ERA in two career starts
against Florida. ... Jose Silva, who leads all active Pirates
pitchers with 32 appearances, makes his first start of the season
Monday in Montreal. ... With Pirates pinch-hitters slumping, with
five hits in their last 41 at-bats through Thursday, manager Gene
Lamont probably won't give John Vander Wal as many spot starts as
before. Vander Wal, who is tied for seventh all-time with 114 pinch
hits, is 6-for-13 with two homers and nine RBIs as a pinch-hitter.
... The Pirates finished 2-5 against the Braves after going 3-4
against them last season.
Braves-Phillies:
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: Andres Galarraga started against Curt Schilling despite
bringing a lifetime average of .100 (4-for-40) against him. ...
Terry Mulholland, who starts Saturday, is 34-25 lifetime at
Veterans Stadium. He had two stints playing with the Phillies. ...
Reggie Sanders started his first game Friday since going on the DL
May 6.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: While the Phillies took batting practice, the 1980
World Series championship team was honored with a parade through
downtown Philadelphia on Friday night. ... The Phillies hired Dan
Roberts, son of Hall of Famer Robin Roberts, to be a coach for
Single-A Batavia. ... Bobby Abreu was not in the starting lineup
Friday because he is 2-for-24 against Tom Glavine.
Mets-Brewers:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: The Mets are tied with the Reds for the NL lead in
one-run victories with 13. ... LHP Mike Hampton (groin) will have
his next start pushed back two days, pitching Tuesday at home
against the Phillies. Rick Reed was scheduled to start Sunday in
the finale of the three-game series in Milwaukee. ... The Mets have
dominated the Brewers, going 16-3 since Milwaukee joined the NL in
1998. New York started the weekend series with eight straight wins
over the Brewers, not losing to Milwaukee since May 18, 1999. ...
Through 63 games this year, the Mets are 35-28. Last year they were
33-30.
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: The Brewers designated seldom-used IF Sean Berry for
assignment, hoping to trade the seven-year veteran as soon as
possible. The Brewers have seven days to trade, release or send
Berry outright to the minors. But Berry, batting .152 (7-for-46),
will not be sent to the minors. ''Sean had no interest in doing
that, nor do we,'' GM Dean Taylor said. ... OF Lyle Mouton was
activated to fill Berry's spot on the roster. ... The Brewers
entered the weekend series with only one victory in nine home games
against the Mets.
Cardinals-Dodgers:
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: Mark McGwire had 23 home runs in the Cardinals' first
65 games, helping them build a 37-28 record and a 4&AMP;frac12;-game lead in
the NL Central. After 65 games in McGwire's record-breaking
70-homer season of 1998, he had 31 home runs -- but the Cardinals
were nine games out of first place with a 31-34 record. Last year,
McGwire had 19 homers through the team's first 65 games, and the
Cardinals were 6 1-2 games off the pace with a 32-33 mark. ... If
the Cardinals hang on to their lead and win the NL Central, La
Russa will join Sparky Anderson (Cincinnati and Detroit) and Whitey
Herzog (Kansas City and St. Louis) as the only managers to win at
least two division titles with two different organizations. La
Russa guided Oakland to four AL West crowns during a five-year
span. An asterisk on that list belongs to Davey Johnson, who
managed the Mets to a pair of NL East titles, and Cincinnati to the
best record in the NL Central during the strike-interrupted 1994
season.
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: The Dodgers optioned newly acquired RHP Al Reyes to
Triple-A Albuquerque and recalled C Adam Melhuse from the Dukes.
''I don't necessarily like to bring a guy in and not even give him
the opportunity to pitch here, but I have no choice,'' Johnson
said. ''I don't need 12 pitchers. Eleven is enough. I don't have
enough innings to keep the whole bullpen sharp because they're not
overworked. And very I'm probably going to need more flexibility
with the catching situation because the rulings on the suspensions
(of Chad Kreuter and the injured Todd Hundley) are coming up (next
week during the series in Houston). That's why I need 14 position
players.''
Diamondbacks-Rockies:
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: 1B Erubiel Durazo took batting practice in Tucson,
Ariz., on Friday for the first time since going on the disabled
list with torn cartilage in his right wrist. The Diamondbacks hope
Durazo can start working out with the team Monday when they return
to Phoenix. ... OF Steve Finley is 0-for-17 in his last five games
and has not driven in a run or homered since June 4. Manager Buck
Showalter is not concerned. ''You couldn't tell if he is 17-for-17
or 0-for-17. He will go down hacking with all guns blazing every
game. No one is going to be in a groove for 162 games. It doesn't
happen.'' ... The Diamondbacks are 4-13 in their last 17 road
games.
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: The Rockies, long known for their power rather than
their speed, is second in the NL with 62 stolen bases. Colorado had
70 steals all of last season, but OF Tom Goodwin could match that
by himself. Goodwin reached 30 steals faster than any player in
Rockies history and is on pace for 78, which would shatter Eric
Young's team record of 53 in 1996. ... Manager Buddy Bell will
alter his starting rotation slightly because of Friday night's
rainout. LHP Brian Bohanon and RHP Masato Yoshii were pushed back a
day, but RHP Pedro Astacio will stay in his scheduled spot Tuesday
at Cincinnati. Sunday's originally scheduled starter, RHP Rolando
Arrojo, will go Wednesday. ... OF Larry Walker wore a Phoenix Suns
jersey under his jacket in batting practice. The jersey had
Walker's favorite No. 33, which was the same number worn by Suns
great Alvin Adams. ''Who's Alvin Adams?'' Walker said.
Reds-Padres:
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: 3B Aaron Boone started Friday night at San Diego for
the first time since he sustained a broken nose when he was hit by
a pitch by Russ Ortiz on Tuesday at San Francisco. ... Aaron Boone
watched older brother Bret's three-run homer sail to left-center
field in the first inning, giving San Diego a 5-1 lead. ... The
Boones' father, Bob, is a special assistant to Reds general manager
Jim Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: The Padres' second-round draft pick, 1B Xavier Nady
of the University of California, visited the Padres on Friday and
took batting practice and grounders. The Padres think it'll be
tough to sign Nady because he had been projected to go in the top
half of the first round but slid down to the second round. Also,
he's represented by Scott Boras, known as a tough negotiator. ''I
would doubt very much that this kid would take second-round money,
but I don't know.'' ... The Padres remain less than $250,000 apart
in talks with their first-round pick, high school LHP Mark Phillips
of Hanover, Pa. When talks started, Phillips requested a $2.5
million signing bonus and the Padres countered with a $2 million
offer. ... RHP Woody Williams, who had an aneurysm in his right
armpit surgically repaired on May 4, threw 60 pitches in a
simulated game and said he felt good. ''Tomorrow is the key, and if
it feels good, it's a positive,'' Williams said. He anticipates
making two rehab starts and hopes to be back in time to start at
Texas on either July 8 or 9, right before the All-Star break.
Astros-Giants:
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: 3B Chris Truby made his major league debut on Friday,
replacing 3B Ken Caminiti, who was placed on the 15-day disabled
list due to a ruptured tendon sheath in his right wrist. ... LHP
Billy Wagner has eight blown saves in his first 14 opportunities.
He blew a total of three save opportunities during the 1999 season.
''I don't think anybody's giving up on Billy,'' manager Larry
Dierker said. ''Obviously we're concerned because he's a much
better pitcher than this. It might be different if he was somebody
that wasn't proven, but Billy is, so he's going to get every chance
to work out of this.'' ... RHP Jose Lima is 1-4 with a 7.19 ERA in
seven road games.
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: Kirk Rueter's wife, Karla, gave birth to Hope
Elaine (8 pounds, 4 ounces, 20&AMP;frac12; inches) on Wednesday. ''It was a
long day, but a perfect day,'' said Rueter. ''The nurses say she
looks like Karla and I hope she's going to take after her.'' It is
the Rueter's first child. ... Dusty Baker celebrated his 51st
birthday on Thursday with a rare day off. ''Usually I'm playing on
my birthday,'' said Baker. ''And like you guys (the media) say,
usually losing. I skipped it this year. Maybe that's a good omen. I
feel recharged.'' The Giants are 1-6 on Baker's birthdays. ... RHP
Livan Hernandez has a 2.83 home ERA.
</P>
