<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN: Rwanda, Uganda Leave Congo  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Concluding two days of talks with Congo's
warring armies, the Security Council demanded that Rwanda and
Uganda immediately withdraw their forces from the country and
threatened to consider sanctions if they don't.
</P>
<P>
   In a unanimously adopted resolution Friday, the council also
said Rwanda and Uganda should pay for the damage and deaths they
inflicted on the northern Congolese city of Kisangani, where they
fought earlier this month, killing an estimated 300 people.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution was adopted at the close of the meeting that
included the foreign ministers of Rwanda, Uganda and Congo and
representatives of the key rebel groups and other foreign armies
involved in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Ugandan Foreign Minister Amama Mbabazi, who chairs a committee
of the various factions, called the meeting a success because all
sides reaffirmed their commitment to Congo's year-old peace
agreement, known as the Lusaka Accord.
</P>
<P>
   ''We therefore go with the confidence that this interaction will
result in faster and effective implementation of Lusaka,'' Mbabazi
told the council.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the two-day session focused on pressing all foreign
forces to leave Congo and encouraging dialogue between the
government and opposition. U.N. officials say such dialogue has
been stymied by repeated obstacles mounted by the government.
</P>
<P>
   The debate among council members on the draft resolution had
focused on whether to demand that Rwanda and Uganda pull out of
Congo before the other foreign armies -- Namibia, Zimbabwe and
Angola -- which are supporting Congolese President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda and Uganda entered the war two years ago, backing
different rebel groups seeking to oust Kabila. They say they are
involved to protect their borders from their own rebels operating
inside Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Rwanda and Uganda turned their guns on each
other in Kisangani. The fighting ended Sunday after Rwandan forces
drove the Ugandans out of the northern sector of the city and let
unarmed U.N. military observers deploy between the former allies.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution demands Rwanda and Uganda and other armed groups
''immediately and completely withdraw from Kisangani'' and from the
entire country ''without further delay'' as called for by the peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   It says the two countries should make reparations ''for the loss
of life and the property damage they have inflicted on the civilian
population in Kisangani'' and asks the United Nations to submit a
report on what the amount should be.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution also says the council would consider possible
''measures'' if the Congo parties fail to abide by the demands in
the resolution -- a reference to possible economic and diplomatic
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ''So long as there is movement there will be some patience in
the Security Council,'' said British Ambassador Jeremy Greenstock.
''If that movement evaporates, then so will our patience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-17-00 0134 </TRAILER>
