<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Allard Baird To Be KC's GM  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Allard Baird will become general manager
of the Kansas City Royals, succeeding Herk Robinson effective
immediately, The Kansas City Star reported.
</P>
<P>
   Baird, 38, has been the team's vice president and assistant
general manager for baseball operations.
</P>
<P>
   New Royals owner David Glass told the Star on Friday that Baird
will be introduced as the new GM before Saturday night's game with
Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson is in his 31st year with the Royals and his 10th as
general manager, giving him the longest tenure of any GM in the
American League. He will remain with the club in his role as chief
operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a very positive thing for the organization,'' said
Glass. ''Everybody's very excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Royals have long been grooming Baird for the role and Glass
views the change as a promotion for him rather than a demotion for
Robinson, 59.
</P>
<P>
   Glass had indicated previously that he wouldn't make any
significant personnel moves until after the season, but decided to
act now because he thinks Baird is ready.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has already begun to do a great deal of the day-to-day
stuff,'' Glass said.
</P>
<P>
   Baird is in his 12th season with the Royals and has spent his
career on the baseball side of the business. He has held jobs from
hitting coach at the minor league level to territorial scouting
supervisor in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   He was named special assistant to the general manager in
February 1997 and promoted to a vice president and assistant GM in
September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is unquestionably time to hand the reins over,'' said
Robinson. ''I have worked closely with Al for the last couple of
years in preparation for this day. He is very, very qualified. He's
a good baseball man. He's at a good stage and age of his life. Lots
of energy, very creative. He's well-respected throughout baseball,
very respected by our own coaches and players.''
</P>
<P>
   Baird will handle all day-to-day baseball operations of the
club.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, who became chief operating officer shortly after Glass
took control of the Royals, will maintain a full-time role with the
team.
</P>
<P>
   Baird and Art Chaudry, senior vice president for business
operations, will both report to Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Glass took control of the Royals on April 28 and less than a
month ago he gave manager Tony Muser a two-year contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   Previously Glass installed his son, Dan, as the club's
president.
</P>
<P>
   ''We view Dan and Baird as being the architects of the future
for the Royals,'' Glass said. ''While Herk and I are here, with all
of our experience, we can help them grow. But Herk and I are from a
different generation.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We are positioning the Royals' next generation of management
to make sure we are comfortable for the foreseeable future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-17-00 0146 </TRAILER>
