<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro 2000 Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By RAF CASERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even the sweetest goals could not prevent Euro 2000 from turning
sour.
</P>
<P>
   After a first week of fun and games, a hooligan riot left a
trail of destruction through Brussels, Belgium, and left 137
Englishmen in jail even before Saturday's kickoff of the game
between Germany and England in Charleroi, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   The skills, beauty and goals displayed by France and the
Netherlands as they qualified for the quarterfinals paled in
comparison with the violence and racist taunts that wrote another
sorry chapter in the history of soccer hooliganism.
</P>
<P>
   France eliminated the Czech Republic with a 2-1 win, and cohost
the Netherlands eliminated Denmark immediately afterwards with a
3-0 thrashing.
</P>
<P>
   Germany and England, both on the ropes in Group A, will be
looking anxiously at the result of group leader Portugal against
Romania, who meet in Arnhem, Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Most eyes unfortunately center on hooligans who ran amok through
the historic center of Brussels leaving a trail of ransacked shops
and bars. A massive police presence was able to detain 137
Englishmen, of whom 35 were charged.
</P>
<P>
   Police anticipated the worst violence would occur in Charleroi
before or after Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen people were hospitalized with injuries after the
riot, which had police cornering and clubbing English hooligans.
</P>
<P>
   In Charleroi, police surrounded the main square where English
fans were drinking, while some were chanting anti-Turkish racist
songs. Police picked some rowdy fans from the crowds and took them
away. An actual fight with police never materialized.
</P>
<P>
   Belgium tightened border controls, and at least two dozen known
hooligans or drunken fans were sent back to England, bringing the
total of people forced to leave since the tournament opened to 56.
It was not enough to stop the violence.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know we have a reputation, but it is not all of us,''
English fan George Scotland said. ''I have a ticket for the
Charleroi game, but it is making me think twice about going.''
</P>
<P>
   Charleroi is 31 miles south of the capital. Most German fans
were expected to go straight to Charleroi on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Rotterdam, meanwhile, was hopping to the rhythm of the Dutch
team.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Kluivert put the Dutch ahead in the 58th minute at a
time when they started showing nerves. Substitute Ronald de Boer
added the second in the 66th soon after entering the game, and
Boudewijn Zenden made it a hat trick for Barcelona players by
adding the third with 12 minutes to go.
</P>
<P>
   ''When halftime arrived and we were goal-less, we weren't very
confident that there would be a good result for us,'' coach Frank
Rijkaard said. ''We knew we had to give a lot more to make pressure
as a collective team. When that happened, we started to play
better.''
</P>
<P>
   France advanced in the tournament with respect for the Czech
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Czechs are one of the toughest sides in the tournament.
They don't deserve to go out,'' said French forward Thierry Henry,
who scored Friday's opener for France.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-17-00 0155 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000617.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinal and Tigers Play for Title  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LONG
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- While LSU's Brad Cresse and Blair Barbier
reminisced about being back in the College World Series final,
Stanford's John Gall, sitting just a few feet away, waited for his
turn.
</P>
<P>
   The LSU players talked about the Tigers' current 12-game winning
streak and what a great run the team had in the 1990s, when it won
four NCAA titles.
</P>
<P>
   Gall wanted to chime in, but held his tongue.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unlike Brad and Blair, we haven't won one. So this is a new
experience for this side of the table,'' Gall said.
</P>
<P>
   A new experience for an old team.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal (50-15), playing in their first CWS championship
game since 1988, have seven upperclassmen in their starting lineup.
They believed it could be the difference in Saturday's title game
against LSU (51-17).
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel good about our chances,'' Stanford senior Edmund Muth
said. ''In every game we've had where it's been lose this and your
career is over, we've responded. Nothing changes here.
</P>
<P>
   ''The foul lines aren't turned any different, the mound's not
any higher, the fences aren't any farther back and they still have
to throw the ball over 17 inches of the plate. And that's where our
experience really should make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers aren't exactly cubs, either.
</P>
<P>
   LSU has eight holdovers from the 1998 team that played at
Rosenblatt Stadium, three of whom also played on the 1997
championship squad.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are the money games,'' LSU first baseman Brad Hawpe
said. ''This is what puts the ring on your finger, and that's what
we're playing for.''
</P>
<P>
   Again.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers were 23-7 at the CWS in the 1990s, including 13-2 in
the last five years. Stanford, making its third appearance in the
championship game, won titles in 1987 and '88.
</P>
<P>
   LSU won four championships in the 1990s, earning the distinction
as the team of the decade. But the Tigers, who are 4-0 in title
games, haven't won one since posting back-to-back titles in 1996
and '97.
</P>
<P>
   LSU is a slightly different team than it was during the '90s
run. The Tigers -- whose style was called ''Gorilla ball'' and who
were nicknamed the ''Baton Rouge Bombers'' for all the homers --
don't have quite the power throughout the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, they set the NCAA Division I record for homers in a
season with 188. This year, with the NCAA-mandated, less-potent
bats, they have 96 dingers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'd get seven or eight hits and a couple of them would be
three-run home runs,'' Barbier said. ''That's how we won.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt still seems to suit the Tigers, though. They have
scored 29 runs in three games and have hit nine home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Cresse, who had 30 home runs this season, is still waiting for
his first at this year's CWS. He snapped a 0-for-9 hitless streak
against Florida State on Thursday, which could prove huge for the
Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was big for me,'' Cresse said. ''It hasn't been a good
tournament for me, but it's been a great one for my team.''
</P>
<P>
   And it still could get better. The Tigers will start Brian
Tallet (15-3) against Stanford. Tallet, a lanky left-hander, hasn't
pitched since last Saturday's opener against Texas. He gave up five
runs in 7 1-3 innings for the win, making him only the third
pitcher in LSU history to win 15 games in a season.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford planned to counter with either right-hander Jason Young
(9-1) or right-hander Justin Wayne (15-3).
</P>
<P>
   Both pitchers were drafted in the early rounds of last week's
amateur draft. Wayne went to the Montreal Expos with the fifth
overall pick, and Young was taken 47th overall by Colorado Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   ''Each of us has a different bag of goodies,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever starts, the other one will be the first Cardinal out of
the bullpen. Stanford also has a dominant closer with Jeff Bruksch,
who is tied for the school record with 13 saves.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is just what we always wanted,'' said Muth, who holds the
CWS career record for home runs with six. ''We've played in every
big game except the big one, and now we're there.
</P>
<P>
   ''But we're not just happy to be here. I don't see any guy on
our team overly excited. We expected to be here, so now let's just
go for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-17-00 0159 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000617.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gibson Leads SBC Championship  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Fred Gibson found the Bermuda grass greens of
Dominion Country Club to his liking.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson had nine birdies in a bogey-free round Friday, shooting a
tournament-record 9-under-par 63 for a 4-stroke lead on the opening
day of the Senior PGA Tour's SBC Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson, 52, made an uphill 12-foot birdie putt on the 545-yard,
par-5 18th green to break the tournament record of 64 set by J.C.
Goosie in 1987 and matched by George Archer in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's nice to see some putts go in,'' said Gibson, who made
seven birdie putts of 10 feet or more. He holed three 30-foot putts
and one 20-footer.
</P>
<P>
   ''The greens are perfect. I'm from Orlando, so I'm very familiar
with Bermuda grass,'' Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of his game also fell into place.
</P>
<P>
   ''I drove the ball real well. It's hard to control it when the
ball is in the rough. This is just the first day. Regardless of the
outcome the rest of this week, I know I'm playing well enough going
into the U.S. Senior Open.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Senior Open begins June 29 in Bethlehem, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Hall, playing despite the pain of three kidney stones,
opened with a 67, good for second place.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've had an interesting week with the kidney stones,'' Hall
said. ''I hit the ball awfully well. I thought about withdrawing
early in the week, but the emergency room doctor told me to take it
one day at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously, I wasn't nearly as sharp as Fred. The course is in
great condition. If you're accustomed to Bermuda greens and can
read the grain correctly, you can make a lot of putts on these
greens.''
</P>
<P>
   Three-time winner Lee Trevino was five strokes back at 68 along
with Ray Floyd and Gary McCord. England's Brian Barnes shot a 69,
and John Mahaffey, the defending champion in his hometown event,
topped an 11-player group at 70.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Dougherty had his first hole-in-one on the senior tour, using
a 6-iron on the 153-yard, par-3 17th hole. It was the ninth ace on
the tour this year and the third in the tournament's 16-year
history. Dougherty opened with a 73.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
