<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, June 17, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Los Alamos Hard Drives Investigated
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Authorities hope to know by late Saturday whether two
computer hard drives found at the Los Alamos weapons laboratory definitely are
the same ones containing nuclear secrets that have been missing for more than a
month. They also will conduct an electronic examination to learn whether the
contents have been copied or otherwise tampered with, said one official,
speaking on condition of anonymity. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson said the
two devices were found within the secure ''Division X'' area of the New Mexico
weapons lab in an area that had been searched previously. Another official, who
spoke on condition of anonymity, said they were discovered behind a copying
machine.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
22 Low Caste India Villagers Killed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Gunmen dressed in black stormed a village in eastern
India and shot dead 22 members of a low caste community, domestic news agencies
reported. The attackers were members of the Ranvir Sena, a private militia run
by upper caste feudal landlords, K.A. Jacob, the police chief in eastern Bihar
state said, quoted by the Press Trust of India. The massacre was apparently in
retaliation for the killing of 12 upper caste villagers last week.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Syria Takes Steps for Bashar Assad
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- The near certainty of Bashar Assad's succession of
his father, President Hafez Assad, gets a fresh boost Saturday when Syria's
ruling Baath party meets to elect him party leader and declare his candidacy for
president. The party conference is part of an official script laid out for
Bashar Assad, a political novice, to fill the vacuum left by the death of his
father after 30 years at the helm of this Arab nation.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Texas A&AMP;M Suspends Bonfire
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas (AP) -- Texas A&AMP;M University is suspending its
traditional pre-game bonfire for at least two more years to give officials time
to improve procedures following an accident last year that killed 12 students.
When the tradition does resume, in 2002 at the earliest, the bonfire will be far
smaller and the construction will be much more professionally run, Texas A&AMP;M
President Ray Bowen said Friday at a news conference. The change resulted from
the collapse during construction of the 2 million-pound log stack Nov. 18.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Jailed Russian Tycoon Released
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- After four days in prison and an outcry accusing the Kremlin
of cracking down on the press, media baron Vladimir Gusinsky was freed, smiling
and thanking the press for their intense coverage of the case. Charges of
swindling and theft are still pending against the 47-year-old tycoon, one of
Russia's most prominent businessmen. A spokesman for the prosecutor-general's
office said Gusinsky was released after promising not to leave the country.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Takes Swipe at Gore's Tax Plan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CANTON, Ohio (AP) -- George W. Bush on Friday suggested Al Gore doubled the
size of his tax cut plan because that's what polling said he should do. ''Surely
America doesn't want a focus group-driven presidency,'' said the GOP contender.
Bush acknowledged his own campaign uses focus groups, which are people chosen
for their characteristics and questioned on specific topics. On Thursday,
Democrat Gore promised $500 billion in tax relief over 10 years to help
middle-class Americans pay for tuition, buy health insurance and save for
retirement. The total is double his earlier estimate, an increase he said was
possible because of a rising federal surplus.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 266; Nasdaq Gains 15
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks fell steeply Friday after Xerox and a
regional banking company issued profit warnings. In its biggest selloff in two
months, the Dow Jones industrial average plunged 265.52 points to close at
10,449.30. On the NYSE, losers led gainers 1,584-1,307. The Nasdaq was up 14.82
at 3,860.56.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pacers Defeat Lakers 120-87
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- On the night they could have been crowned champions, the
Los Angeles Lakers had their most lopsided loss of the season. Led by Jalen
Rose, the Pacers took control early and never let up, keeping the Lakers'
championship plans on hold. Starting 6-for-6 on 3-pointers and making 75 percent
of their shots in the first quarter, Indiana manhandled Los Angeles 120-87
Friday night in Game 5 of the NBA Finals.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tiger Woods Leads 100th U.S. Open
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- The fog lifted over Pebble Beach on Friday and
revealed the passing of a generation -- Jack Nicklaus limping home in his final
U.S. Open, Tiger Woods breezing along on a brutally tough day. Nicklaus bid an
emotional and unforgettable farewell to 44 years in the toughest championship in
golf, reaching the 545-yard 18th hole in two shots. Woods rolled in a 30-foot
putt on the par-3 12th, his fifth birdie of the day on rock-hard greens, to get
to 9 under for the tournament and build a three-shot lead over Miguel Angel
Jimenez.
</P>
