<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Open Notebook  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL NEWBERRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- The regulars of the Senior PGA Tour
were holding their own with the youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   All four -- Tom Watson, Hale Irwin, Dave Eichelberger and Tom
Kite -- were projected to make the cut after the second round was
completed Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Eichelberger, the defending U.S. Senior Open champion, rebounded
from an opening-round 78 to shoot a 2-under 69. It was one of only
four below-par scores among players who finished their rounds
before darkness postponed play Friday evening. The average score
for the day: 76.024.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's as good a round as I've played in a long, long time,''
Eichelberger, 56, said. ''Even when I won the Senior Open, I don't
think I played that good.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson had the best two-round score among the Seniors, a 3-over
145. Irwin, who briefly contended for the lead, was at 146 and Kite
149.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess it shows the old boys can still do it,'' Eichelberger
said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, 55, had one of the most surprising scores of the first
round, a 3-under 68 that left him only three shots behind leader
Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   But Irwin, who completed the round Friday morning after fog
halted play the previous day, had only a half-hour break before
going back to the first tee to start another 18 holes. It proved to
be too much for his back, already sore since he strained a ligament
at a Senior event in Atlanta last month.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin shot a 7-over 78 in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ''The more we stood around, the tighter it got,'' he said,
having spent nearly eight hours on the course. ''It was tight as a
drum. It showed on my shots. I didn't hit it very far.''
</P>
<P>
   The low point of the round was a double-bogey 6 at No. 16. Irwin
missed the fairway with a 4-wood off the tee and was forced to
pitch out from the high rough. He had an 8-iron to the green, but
came up short, forcing him to chip on for a 2-putt.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a quick double-bogey,'' Irwin said. ''I never really
felt like I hit a bad shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Irwin became the oldest player to win the Open,
beating Mike Donald in a playoff in Medinah, Ill. He won't be
breaking that record at Pebble Beach, but the old-timers have
nothing to be ashamed of.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   HANGING ON: Bobby Clampett slipped off his spikes before he
even got to the locker room, easing the pain from the blisters on
his heels. It was a hard day at the U.S. Open -- and he only played
16 holes.
</P>
<P>
   Clampett, the golfer-turned-broadcaster-turned-golfer, struggled
through a four-bogey, no-birdie round before darkness halted play
about 8:15 p.m. PDT. That left him 1-over par after an
opening-round 68.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very difficult conditions,'' he said. ''The golf course
is beating you up right now. If you hit a good shot, it's par. If
you hit a bad shot, it's bogey.''
</P>
<P>
   Clampett blamed a faulty putter for his troubles. He hit the
first seven greens in regulation, but had only a bogey and six pars
to show for it. After that, the rest of his game began to suffer.
He finished up with a bogey at No. 16 after hitting his tee shot
behind a tree.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, though, not a bad showing for a golfer who has played
only one tournament in two years, spending most of his time as a
broadcaster for CBS.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's still some things in my game that are a little
rusty,'' said Clampett, playing the Open for the first time in 14
years. ''You've got to expect that.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   AMATEUR WOES: David Gossett came to the U.S. Open with more
confidence than one would expect from a 21-year-old collegian. Then
again, he won the U.S. Amateur championship last year on the same
course.
</P>
<P>
   But Pebble Beach proved to be a little tougher this time for the
University of Texas student.
</P>
<P>
   Gossett, low amateur at the Masters in April, couldn't get
anything going in his return trip to the northern California coast.
He finished with rounds of 78 and 77 for a 13-over total.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had so many positive memories from this place,'' he said.
''I played well here. I was comfortable here. So, yeah, I'm
disappointed. But golf is a fickle game, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Finishing up his first round Friday morning, Gossett got a taste
of Pebble Beach's wicked side at the par-3 17th -- the same hole
where Tom Watson made his famous birdie from the rough in winning
the 1982 Open.
</P>
<P>
   Gossett needed four shots just to get on the green. His first
shot landed in the back rough off the tee, and his next shot found
a bunker on the right side. He blasted out of the sand to the first
cut of rough on the left side.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Gossett ditched his jacket, perhaps hoping that
would change his luck. He pitched within 5 feet of the flag and
made the putt for a double-bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ''Since it's summer, I don't have to go back to classes,'' said
Gossett, who is majoring in communications. ''I'll spend some time
working on my game.''
</P>
<P>
   At least he has the memory of playing with Jack Nicklaus.
Gossett was pared with the Golden Bear for the final round at
Augusta, followed by the first two rounds of the Open. Next month,
he'll complete a remarkable year by playing the British Open at St.
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   COSTON THE COMEDIAN: Jeff Coston, playing in the Open for the
first time since 1978, shot a 6-over 77 in the second round. At
least he could laugh about it.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his 3-iron on the par-3 17th, he replied, ''I
hit a good one into the air. I was going to run under it. I thought
the infield fly rule was in effect.''
</P>
<P>
   The 44-year-old Coston, who shot a 70 in the first round, wasn't
done. Here's a sampling of his other comments:
</P>
<P>
   --''I don't know where I am. Somebody touch me and wake me up.''
</P>
<P>
   --''I don't see the ball as well (as 22 years ago). I went to my
optometrist to get that laser surgery and he said it's too late for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   --''I tried too hard, took too long and thought too much. Maybe I
needed a lobotomy.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   PAULSON OUT: Dennis Paulson withdrew after the second round,
citing back and rib injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Paulson came to the Open on a roll, having won his first PGA
Tour event the previous week in the Buick Classic. He beat David
Duval in a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   But Paulson dropped out after rounds of 75 and 76 at Pebble
Beach, a 9-over score that was in danger of missing the cut anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
