<HEADLINE> Colo. Firefighters Making Progress  </HEADLINE>
By STEVE GUTTERMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAILEY, Colo. (AP) -- With another cold, damp day in the forecast
Saturday, firefighters in the Colorado foothills were working
furiously to hem in two wildfires that blackened more than 20,000
acres in a five-day rampage.
</P>
<P>
   Jubilant residents were allowed back into their homes east of
Rocky Mountain National Park. ''I not only kissed the ground, but I
think I ate some ashes,'' said Tom Larrance.
</P>
<P>
   Rain, snow and temperatures in the 30s helped keep flames at bay
Friday while crews quickly cut fire lines around the perimeter of
the blazes. By the end of the day, both fires were 50 percent
contained.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not dead,'' warned Mike Reasor, a spokesman for the team
managing one of the fires. ''It has the potential to get up and go
again if we don't take advantage of the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunny weather was expected to return Sunday, increasing the risk
that the fires could roar back to life. ''It's going to be warming
up and it's going to drying out,'' said Mike Chamberlain, a
meteorologist with the management team.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities also identified a suspect who may have started the
fire while camping in the area. They said the 33-year-old Loveland
resident, Kenny Winchester, has retained a lawyer and refused to
talk with sheriff's deputies.
</P>
<P>
   Both fires started Monday and spread quickly, propelled by hot,
dry winds. At least 39 homes were destroyed and more than 400
people were forced to flee. All were allowed to go home by Friday
except for 35 families in the Bailey area, southwest of Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's great to have everybody home,'' said Kevin Corbett, who
had stayed behind to guard against looters while his wife and her
son evacuated their house in Conifer. ''These last few days have
been a little like house arrest. It's great to get the neighborhood
back to normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Fire managers estimated the cost of fighting both blazes had
climbed to more than $3.8 million. Nearly 1,900 firefighters were
on the scene by week's end, and helicopters and tanker planes had
made scores of runs to drop water and fire-retardant slurry.
</P>
<P>
   The blazes are the latest in what is shaping up as the nation's
worst fire season since 1996. The National Interagency Fire Center
in Idaho reported that more than 45,000 fires this season have
burned 1.2 million acres.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Interagency Fire Center: http://www.nifc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson County Sheriff's Office map:
http://www.co.jefferson.co.us/fire/himeadow4.jpg
</P>
<P>
   Rocky Mountain Area Coordinating Group:
http://www.fs.fed.us/r2/fire/rmcghome.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
