<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reform Party members say they're for real, experts say not yet  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - It had all the trappings of a political
convention: sign waving, slogan shouting and speech making.
</P>
<P>
   But when it came time to cast votes, party organizers passed
around cardboard boxes.
</P>
<P>
   The left side of the room got one with a handwritten sign taped
to it; those on the right made do with one from an office supply
store.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the Reform Party's state convention, where
conventioneers were as likely to stumble past community college
students in the hallway as they would their candidates for
president or U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Reform Party claim it is just as viable as the
two major political organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Forget tales of infighting and images of fringe candidates. If
New Jersey voters could hear the party's message, they would
respond by putting Reform candidates in office, said party
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're a small party, no doubt about it, but we're going to
build it,'' said Joe Sansone. ''I think the Reform Party is
becoming America's party.''
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party activists point to New Jersey's significant share
of registered Independent voters. And they highlight Libertarian
Murray Sabrin's 1997 run for governor where his 6 percent of the
vote made him eligible for public campaign funding.
</P>
<P>
   But others say independent or third parties like the Reform
Party clearly are steps behind Republicans and Democrats. Political
analysts contend that it is more than just a gap in funding or
organization. Many third party candidates and their messages lack
credibility, analysts charge.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Sansone was approved as state chairman for the
party that formed after Ross Perot's failed presidential campaigns.
Sansone now heads New Jersey's organization working to elect
Patrick Buchanan president.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, the conservative talk show host, joins Pat DiNizio,
the singer who put rock band The Smithereens on hold to run for
U.S. Senate, at the top of the Reform Party ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Both men say the enthusiasm exhibited at the state convention
proves theirs is a burgeoning movement.
</P>
<P>
   If a member of a traditional party had that kind of energy
before the Iowa presidential caucus, the national media would
consider that candidate a contender, Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're seeing the kind of energy and excitement that you would
see in the Iowa Caucus about a month out,'' Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   DiNizio said he was encouraged not only by the enthusiasm, but
the commitment by such a wide range of people.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the passion. I find it remarkable that so many people
would be here at this time of day,'' DiNizio said after the
Wednesday afternoon convention at Raritan Valley Community College.
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party allows people the option of not just another
candidate, but the chance to be come involved in the process,
DiNizio said. And it is not dedicated to a single special interest
or fringe group, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't believe the Reform Party is such a party,'' DiNizio
said. ''I think it is a real thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Logue said he is a party activist because he agrees with the
Reform Party's opposition to international trade treaties, strict
gun control and its support of strong border defense. And the party
is attracting more and more people put off by major parties and
their candidates, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have centrists. We have former Republicans and former
Democrats. It is a party that brings all sides in,'' Logue said.
</P>
<P>
   These nontraditional parties all hope to collect at least the
roughly 15 percent of the vote that usually goes to independent
candidates, said Ingrid Reed, the director of the Eagleton
Institute's New Jersey Project.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems to me you have the potential of voters' paying
attention. Then the question is the candidate's credibility, is the
message credible,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it is really hard to know where a third party can go,
because you do have this new complication of what message the
candidate sends. It's hard to tell if they're credible, or the
credibility of the message,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A Reform Party candidate might win in New Jersey, Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   ''But it's still a stretch,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   More likely a strong independent candidate would pull voters
from a major candidate and skew the election, Reed explained.
</P>
<P>
   ''If an election is close, as they are in New Jersey, a strong
third-party candidate can do that,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
