<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buffalo regains crown as upstate New York's No. 1 job hub  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - After a one-month hiatus, a hiring surge
moved Buffalo back ahead of Rochester as the biggest job hub in
upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the two-county Buffalo region registered a record
564,100 jobs, 1,600 more than the tally in the six-county Rochester
region, the state Labor Department said.
</P>
<P>
   Rochester overtook Buffalo as the No. 1 employment center for
the first time in April, but Buffalo bounced back last month with a
seasonal surge in hiring at construction and service companies.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo's unemployment rate fell to 4.4 percent, its lowest
level in May in at least 26 years.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo's employment count has stagnated in the last decade
while Rochester's has surged. The upstate labor market is dwarfed
by the New York metropolitan region's 4.2 million jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department includes Monroe, Wayne, Ontario,
Livingston, Genesee and Orleans counties in the Rochester region
and Erie and Niagara counties in the Buffalo region.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo region's population stands at around 1.2 million,
about 100,000 more people than live in the Rochester area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-17-00 1155 </TRAILER>
