<DOCNO> APW20000617.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP on TV: Animal Planet  </HEADLINE>
By BRIDGET RNE
For The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Need an adrenaline rush? Want to laugh? Feel
like a good cry? ''Animal Planet'' -- that all-animals-all-the-time
cable channel -- is fulfilling the emotional needs of an increasing
number of human viewers.
</P>
<P>
   According to the A.C. Nielsen Co., the Discovery Channel spinoff
is growing faster than any other cable outlet. Launched in October
1996, Animal Planet now attracts over 60 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Around-the-clock viewers of all ages obsess over creatures great
and small, from tough old crocs with very sharp teeth to precious
little pussycats with bruised paws.
</P>
<P>
   ''It allows for the full emotional range ... but it also speaks
to the head as well as to the heart,'' says Clark Bunting,
executive vice president and general manager of the Bethesda,
Md.-based Animal Planet.
</P>
<P>
   Bunting says the channel is committed to offering shows that are
entertaining and educational, but also safe for the whole family to
watch -- no less a challenge in the animal kingdom than it is with
people programming.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, sex and violence can be issues for even Animal Planet, and
Bunting says it all ''boils down to common sense and good
judgment'' when deciding how much of the wild world to show, how
much fur to let fly.
</P>
<P>
   ''Kids watching need to know that animals kill, die and have
sex,'' said Bunting. ''It's part of the natural order ... but we
never hold shots gratuitously or for shock value.''
</P>
<P>
   Family values haven't taken any bite out of the network's
super-popular ''Crocodile Hunter,'' which has made international
stars out of critter-chasing Australian Steve Irwin and his
American wife, Terri.
</P>
<P>
   The show's second annual ''Croc Week'' begins Sunday (June 18)
at 8 p.m. Eastern, including the harrowing new episodes ''Spitting
Cobras,'' ''Crocs of the Revolution'' and ''Dangerous Africans.''
</P>
<P>
   All feature Irwin in seemingly imminent danger of being -- as he
says in the autobiographical ''Steve's Story'' episode -- ''gored,
clawed, chomped, bitten, savaged, jumped on, whacked, peed on and
even groped'' by a variety of creatures most people would run a
mile from.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Steve, Terri and top croc Agro will be available as action
figures, with built-in audio of such Steve lingo as ''By crikey''
and ''What a ripper.'' Toys, games, Web site linkage and plans for
a theme park are all part of ''Animal Planet's'' continued
outreach.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of being a doll is ''mind-boggling,'' said Terri by
phone from the couple's zoo in Queensland. But she believes Steve,
who was off in the bush at the time getting footage of rare birds,
is ''a real-life action hero, totally, passionately, devoted to
saving wildlife, and people respond to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Terri suggested that another reason for Animal Planet's
popularity is the correlation between animal and human behavior
which, for example, might attract ''ER'' lovers to the channel's
''Emergency Vets.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I've not had a scientific approach to animals myself,'' Terri
said. ''I'm much more anthropomorphic. I believe they feel
happiness, sadness, all the emotions like we do, and I think more
and more people are coming to that belief.''
</P>
<P>
   John Stainton, producer of Irwin's series, says Irwin's
''wonderful sense of story telling,'' attracts audiences who might
otherwise be watching sports or surfing the Net. He stresses that
although Irwin ''has no fear,'' care is taken to include messages
about appropriate behavior around wild animals, as in don't try
this at home.
</P>
<P>
   While some conservationists may have reservations about
''Crocodile Hunter'' or some of the dumbed-down aspects of ''Animal
Planet,'' they also acknowledge the channel's plus side.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is something good to be said about anything which
provides people with the knowledge that there are other animals
beside themselves on this planet,'' says John Lukas, director of
the White Oak Plantation Conservation Center, in Yulee, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't please everyone 100 percent, but very early on we
established relationships with humane societies, wildlife funds and
conservationists,'' says Bunting. He cited the ''Animal Planet
Rescue'' vehicle, which has provided animal aid during such
disasters as the 1998 Florida wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Irwins, other human celebrities home grown on
''Animal Planet'' include Dr. Robert Taylor and the other
caregivers of ''Emergency Vets,'' who combine the gurney-racing
treatment for ailing animals with comfort and compassion for people
whose pets don't make it.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, co-founder of Denver's Alameda East hospital, where the
heart-tugging series is shot, has a simple explanation for the
network's success: ''People just love animals, and that feeling
seems to be growing, and 'Animal Planet' just got in touch with
that feeling at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   In its early days, ''Animal Planet'' filled many hours with old
episodes of ''Lassie'' and recycled documentaries. Now, almost 80
percent of its programming is original. In addition to ''Crocodile
Hunter'' and ''Emergency Vets,'' the lineup includes the game show
''You Lie Like a Dog,'' ''Planet's Funniest Animals,'' ''The Ape
Crusaders,'' ''Animal Court'' and the fictional series ''Call of
the Wild,'' based on the Jack London novel.
</P>
<P>
   ''Call of the Wild'' has made a star out of Kavic, a 140-pound
Malamute-timber wolf mix.
</P>
<P>
   ''He gets more fan mail than I do,'' admits Shane Meier, who
stars as Miles Challenger, Buck's owner. ''He can really act.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
