<DOCNO> APW20000617.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 12:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N. Korea Leader Motives Analyzed  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The pictures were compelling: The wide smiles,
the intense jocularity, the let's-bury-the-hatchet demeanor. But
did Kim Jong Il, the North Korean leader, really mean it?
</P>
<P>
   Among Korea watchers in the United States, hope is mixed with a
strong dose of skepticism that North Korea, virtually overnight,
could turn its back on 50 years of hostility toward its southern
neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Former Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., an experienced Asia hand,
agrees that Kim's summit meeting this past week with South Korean
President Kim Dae-jung was an extraordinary development.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, ''There is ample reason to be very cautious
about the lions having laid down with the lambs.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Peter Brooke, East Asia expert on the House International
Relations Committee staff, ''I don't think Kim Jong Il has
undergone an epiphany.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Eberstat of the American Enterprise Institute has his
qualms as well while acknowledging it was refreshing to hear North
Korea refer to the head of South Korea as ''president.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They always maintained that South Korea was a monster with no
legitimate right to exist,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other analysts, Eberstat worries about whether Kim Jong
Il plans to carry out his promises to work toward peaceful
reunification with the South and toward reuniting long-divided
families.
</P>
<P>
   He said Kim Jong Il may have been at his wily best at the
summit.
</P>
<P>
   ''A shaky North Korean system has just negotiated a huge
infusion of foreign aid without making any concessions on nuclear
issues,'' Eberstat said, alluding to the $450 million Seoul has
budgeted this year in assistance to Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   William Drennan, a Korea expert at the U.S. Institute of Peace,
said it is hard to reconcile Kim Jong Il's charm offensive at the
Pyongyang summit with what Drennan describes as the leader's
disreputable past.
</P>
<P>
   Drennan and other experts cited strong evidence of Kim Jong Il's
role as the mastermind of a terrorist bombing of a South Korean
passenger plane that killed 115 people when it crashed off the
Myanmar coast on Nov. 29, 1987.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea long has held the North Korean leader, then in a
subordinate position, responsible for the attack but has muted that
issue as part of Kim Dae-jung's efforts at accommodation.
</P>
<P>
   Drennan also cited other aspects of Kim Jong Il's rule, carried
over from the era of his late father and longtime North Korean
leader, President Kim Il Sung.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that North Korean diplomats routinely have been caught
selling illicit drugs and contraband cigarettes and trading in
counterfeit money. At home, Kim Jong Il presides over what is
widely regarded as one of world's most repressive and economically
deprived states.
</P>
<P>
   Solarz has a sense of deja vu about the agreements signed last
week. He recalled the high hopes generated on Dec. 13, 1991, when
the two sides signed an ''Agreement on Reconciliation,
Nonaggression and Exchanges and Cooperation Between the South and
the North.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the agreements were never implemented ''because of the
recalcitrance and intransigence of Pyongyang.''
</P>
<P>
   The new agreements contemplate far more people-to-people
contacts between South and North, and Solarz again wonders what
Pyongyang is up to.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that thousands of South Koreans visit the North's most
spectacular tourist site, Diamond Mountain, each year but under
conditions imposed by the North that preclude any contact with
ordinary North Koreans.
</P>
<P>
   ''One has to wonder whether they are really prepared to do an
about-face,'' Solarz said.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials harbor similar reservations about North
Korea's willingness to fulfill its promises but have been generally
upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today is a new day of hope for the future of the Korean
Peninsula,'' Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said Thursday.
''The historic summit between the leaders of South and North Korea
represents a bold step toward resolving a half-century of conflict
there.''
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of building on momentum generated at the summit, the
administration is expected to implement on Monday measures that
will ease 50 years of economic sanctions against North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton announced the policy in September. The
administration has delayed the required follow-up action, pending a
demonstration of good will by the North. Kim Jong Il satisfied that
condition last week at the summit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-17-00 1221 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
