<DOCNO> APW20000617.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court Rulings Awaited  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court soon will end its 1999-2000
term with a flurry of rulings sure to have a profound effect on
American life in cases covering abortion, school prayer, gays in
the Boy Scouts and police Miranda warnings.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Monday and within the next two weeks, the court also is
expected to rule on government help for parochial schools,
free-speech rights of abortion protesters and how states conduct
primary elections.
</P>
<P>
   Announcement of just a dozen decisions stand between the
justices and the three-month summer recess they are expected to
begin by June 28. Among them could be rulings that bring dramatic
changes in the law.
</P>
<P>
   In its first ruling on abortion since 1992, the court is
expected to say whether Nebraska can ban a surgical procedure
opponents call ''partial-birth abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the decision says, it is sure to escalate the
decades-old nationwide political war over the legality and morality
of abortion. More immediately, the decision might also control the
fate of similar laws in 29 other states.
</P>
<P>
   School prayer has bedeviled the court for 40 years, and the
justices now are to decide in a Texas case whether public school
districts can let students lead stadium crowds in prayer before
high school football games.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling is certain to be scrutinized to determine whether the
court strongly reaffirms or retreats from a landmark 1962 decision
that outlawed organized, officially sponsored prayer in public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   On a docket extraordinarily full of emotion-packed cases, none
has proved more evocative than a New Jersey gay rights dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The justices must decide whether the Boy Scouts can bar
homosexuals from serving as troop leaders. The decision also may
answer whether boys who say they are gay can be banned as well.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no Supreme Court decision is as well-known as one called
Miranda vs. Arizona, in which the court said police must warn
criminal suspects of their ''right to remain silent'' when
questioned.
</P>
<P>
   Now the court is considering, in a case from Maryland, whether
it should dismantle that 1966 landmark and scuttle the warnings
made familiar to generations of Americans by movies and television.
</P>
<P>
   A church-state dispute from Louisiana asks the court to decide
whether taxpayer money can be used to buy computers and other
instructional materials for religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   Its ruling will affect federal efforts to connect every American
classroom with the Internet and also could carry significance for
the politically charged legal fights over tuition vouchers -- help
for families who send their children to religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   The court is deciding in a California case whether states
violate political parties' free-association rights when they allow
primary election voters to cast their ballot for any candidate
regardless of affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   The justices also are deciding whether Colorado violated
anti-abortion demonstrators' rights when it enacted in 1993 a
''bubble'' law that barred people from counseling, distributing
leaflets or displaying signs within eight feet of others without
their consent whenever they are within 100 feet of a health clinic
entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Also on tap:
</P>
<P>
   --A Colorado River water-use fight between consumers in Arizona
and Southern California on one side and an Indian tribe on the
other.
</P>
<P>
   --An Indiana dispute over federal court oversight of state
prisons.
</P>
<P>
   --A big-money battle over an oil-and-gas deal that never
materialized off North Carolina's Outer Banks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-17-00 1222 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000617.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hezbollas Threaten To Attack  </HEADLINE>
By ZEINA KARAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Hezbollah guerrillas who have fought
Israeli forces in southern Lebanon for 18 years warned Saturday
that they will resume attacks if Israel does not give up tracts of
land claimed by Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ''All violations should be dealt with; ... otherwise we consider
the mission of liberating Lebanese territory to be incomplete and
resistance remains our choice to liberate the last inch of our
occupied land,'' Hezbollah said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The statement came a day after U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan, scheduled Monday to visit Lebanon as part of a Middle East
tour, confirmed Israel's withdrawal from south Lebanon ''in full
compliance'' with Security Council resolution 425.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Salim Hoss on Friday rejected the United Nations'
verification of Israel's May 24 withdrawal, saying Israeli forces
still controlled some parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Hoss renewed Lebanon's commitment to cooperate with
the United Nations ''to the extreme.'' But he added that Lebanon
''insists on recovering every inch of its territory.''
</P>
<P>
   In its statement, Hezbollah described Annan's announcement as
''unrealistic and premature,'' saying it favored Israel. ''We
regret that the United Nations has become a cover for the
continuation of the Zionists' occupation of parts of Lebanese
territory.''
</P>
<P>
   The government and Hezbollah's rejection of the U.N. withdrawal
verification prolongs the risk of renewed cross-border fighting and
is likely to delay the deployment of Lebanese army troops in
southern Lebanon, where the anti-Israel guerrillas are the de facto
authority.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, Annan's formal declaration of the withdrawal
paves the way for the 4,500-strong U.N. peacekeeping mission in
Lebanon to deploy to the Lebanese-Israeli border and help the
Lebanese government reassert its authority in the vacated
territory.
</P>
<P>
   But U.N. spokesman Timur Goksel said Saturday that no
peacekeepers will be deployed before matters are sorted out with
the Lebanese government, possibly during talks Monday with Annan.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has been said all along that Lebanese consent is a
prerequisite of U.N. deployment in any place in the country. After
all, the peacekeeping force is subject to their sovereignty,'' he
told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The government maintains that Lebanese officers working with a
U.N. inspection team found that Israeli troops still manned several
positions inside Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The new border line was drawn by U.N. cartographers according to
the 1923 line fixed by colonial France and Britain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-17-00 1224 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000617.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 12:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syrians Seek Progress With Bashar  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA ABU-NASR
<TEXT>
<P>
   QARDAHA, Syria (AP) -- From the picturesque village of the late
President Hafez Assad to Syria's desert villages to Damascus' old
souks, Syrians are putting together a wish list for Bashar Assad,
the man all but certain to succeed his father as the country's
leader.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd like him to bring us the Internet,'' said Abeer Ismail, a
25-year-old nurse in Qardaha who has taken a computer course in
hopes of a better-paid job. ''Then I'll skimp on makeup and clothes
to save for a computer.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I want feed for my 200 goats and running water at home,'' said
Hashem al-Ghazi, 62, at the desert village of El-Bureij, where
water has been cut for three years.
</P>
<P>
   ''Less bureaucracy, fewer import-export forms to fill out,''
said Mahmoud al-Qadmani, 32, who runs a textile shop in Damascus'
Hamidiyyeh souk.
</P>
<P>
   The wishes are not new. Syrians for years have hoped for a more
dynamic economy, more job opportunities, higher incomes and access
to the latest technology.
</P>
<P>
   But many believe their long-deferred dreams are closer to being
realized because they see Bashar Assad, a 34-year-old eye doctor,
as a young leader better able to understand their aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   Syria's ruling Baath Party opened its first conference in 15
years Saturday to elect Bashar Assad party leader and declare his
candidacy for president, putting him closer to succeeding his
father. Assad's formal election is not expected to be held before
the traditional 40-day mourning period ends July 20.
</P>
<P>
   Syria already has come a long way from the 1960s, when the
government adopted an economy based on a staid socialist system and
nationalized all large industries, including banks and public
utilities.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Hafez Assad began allowing private investment in
agriculture and industry. Then in May 1991, parliament passed what
has become Syria's economic mantra, Law No. 10 -- designed to
attract investment by giving tax holidays of up to nine years,
customs exemptions on machinery and the right to repatriate
profits.
</P>
<P>
   With the adoption of the law, Syria's socialist identity began
to diminish.
</P>
<P>
   The days when getting a bag of bread meant standing in line for
hours are gone. CDs are more prevalent. Mobile phones and credit
cards are slowly becoming part of life. Even satellite dishes,
which still are not legal, sit on balconies next to flower pots.
</P>
<P>
   Modernizing has been slow, however, hampered by antiquated trade
and banking laws and red tape. This has dampened the excitement of
investors who rushed to put their money into projects soon after
Law No. 10 was enacted. That, coupled with low oil prices before
last year, has slowed annual economic growth to less than 3 percent
since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Change hasn't reached all aspects of Syrian life.
</P>
<P>
   Computers are available in shops, and a quasi-governmental
Syrian Computer Society trains ordinary Syrians in computer skills
and runs computer labs for the public in villages and urban
centers. But Internet access is limited to government offices and
the elite.
</P>
<P>
   The educational system remains geared toward producing civil
servants rather than entrepreneurs, computer specialists or experts
who can handle a private sector economy. The unemployment rate for
Syria's 4 million working-age adults is estimated at 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nabil Sukkar, a former World Bank economist who runs a private
investment and development firm in Damascus, said education should
be one of the new regime's top priorities, especially since half
Syria's 17 million people are younger than 20.
</P>
<P>
   Some 200,000 young people enter the labor force every year.
</P>
<P>
   Economic reform ''has to find ways to absorb all this new
generation into society in a productive way, find them employment,
involve them in the future of the country,'' Sukkar said.
</P>
<P>
   Bashar Assad has already started a push for modernization. He is
leading an anti-corruption campaign that has targeted top
government officials. He has said he'd like to see a computer in
every house and followed through with a drive that allows Syrians
who cannot afford computers to buy them from government agencies by
paying small monthly installments. He is also behind a campaign to
computerize government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Sukkar said Assad's mission ''is not going to be easy, but I
think it's doable.''
</P>
<P>
   He expects this week's congress of the ruling Baath Party to
elect a new leadership that will support Assad's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to see new faces more in tune with the times,
younger, less entrenched in the past, more progressive,'' Sukkar
said. ''All this is going to help Dr. Bashar move forward with
economic reforms.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
