<HEADLINE> Toddler swept through 34-foot-long pipe after downpour  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   OSWEGO, N.Y. (AP) - A 2-1/2-year-old boy who was watching frogs
prance around after a rainstorm fell into a ditch at the bottom of
the family's driveway and got sucked into a 34-foot-long drainpipe
by swift-flowing water.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Oleyourryk's father, who was standing nearby, jumped in
to try and grab him but the boy had already vanished down the
foot-wide pipe. A teen-age neighbor ran to the other end of the
pipe, jumped in the ditch and shouted ''I got him!''
</P>
<P>
   The boy was pulled clear, suffering a bad scare but no more than
a few cuts and bruises.
</P>
<P>
   The boy had been watching the frogs Thursday evening with his
4-year-old brother, Jacob, when he fell into the ditch, which runs
along both sides of the driveway and is connected by a pipe under
the driveway. The ditch was filled with muddy water after a
downpour in this town northwest of Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel was gasping for air at first but started crying within
seconds. He was taken to a hospital as a precaution but is doing
fine, said his father, David Oleyourryk.
</P>
</TEXT>
