<HEADLINE> Balkans Still Await Reconstruction  </HEADLINE>
By PATRICK QUINN
<TEXT>
<P>
   THESSALONIKI, Greece (AP) -- The bombs stopped falling on
Yugoslavia a year ago. But Balkan nations are still waiting for the
money promised by the West.
</P>
<P>
   Despite numerous conferences and reams of plans, both supporters
and critics are starting to wonder whether Balkan reconstruction
efforts will remain mostly talk and no action.
</P>
<P>
   ''Promises must be kept,'' insisted Bodo Hombach, coordinator of
the international Stability Pact for the Balkans, which took part
in another planning meeting June 7-9 in the northern Greek city of
Thessaloniki. ''We have to fight against red tape and
bureaucracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hombach frets about a ''downward spiral of disappointment and
failure'' if big donor nations begin losing interest and political
support for their grand promises for Balkan reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   The Stability Pact was formed one year ago with much fanfare by
the European Union, 44 other nations, the World Bank and 36
international organizations. Its goal is to coordinate
international efforts to supply much-needed funds to help promote
economic development in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Its indirect mandate is to add weight to the West's pressure on
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic by cutting Serbia out of most
of the redevelopment projects. Pact members say Serbia can join the
fold as soon as Milosevic is gone from power.
</P>
<P>
   Stability Pact officials also claim that, despite the funding
delays, a major accomplishment so far has been allowing some level
of common purpose in a region of deep ethnic hostilities and
suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   The organization's spokesman, Andrew Levi, called it a
''remarkable change.''
</P>
<P>
   One example, he said, was Hombach's mediation earlier this year
in convincing Romania and Bulgaria to finalize nearly 10 years of
negotiations and agree to build a second bridge over the Danube
River, which defines most of their common border. Construction has
not yet started.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the Pact has not made much real headway in
pumping serious Western investment into the region.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will stagnate like a backwater and it will grow even
worse,'' said Thanos Veremis, president of the Hellenic Foundation
for Defense and Foreign Policy in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Veremis sees the Pact's inability to directly supply funds as a
reflection of waning international interest in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ''Generally it shows the reluctance of all to put their hands in
their pockets,'' Veremis said. ''The Balkans is not a rich place,
it is not strategic or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   International donors in March pledged $2.4 billion to the
Stability Pact, which has already come up with 50 immediate
projects such as road repairs, bridges, power grids and water
supply networks. The agency also seeks to help independent media in
places such as Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   But to get the money, the Stability Pact has to go through a
long tender process and none of the major projects have gotten off
the ground. Officials say the extended process is often necessary
to guard against corruption.
</P>
<P>
   It took EU planners 42 weeks to draw up plans to approve $19.9
million in May to help clear the Danube of debris and unexploded
shells left over from NATO's bombing campaign. But that project is
still pending approval from the 15-nation EU as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Stability Pact officials have indicated they would like to cut
the time for such projects to 16 weeks if possible.
</P>
<P>
   The exclusion from the Pact of Yugoslavia -- a major trade route
for the Balkans -- is another problem. Without Yugoslavia, for
example, the project to clear the Danube will not be enough to
restore full commerce on the waterway since it passes through the
heart of the republic.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is much frustration, and much of this frustration is due
to the black hole called Yugoslavia,'' said Javier Solana, a former
NATO secretary-general who is now the EU's commissioner for
security issues.
</P>
<P>
   Proposals by some EU countries to lift sanctions have been
sidelined. Members of the Yugoslav opposition, who have counted on
help from the West, say lifting sanctions would be an important
step.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the only thing that might help the opposition,'' said
Predrag Simic, foreign policy adviser to opposition leader Vuk
Draskovic, who was nearly killed in a shooting Friday. He blamed
allies of Milosevic for the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Non-governmental organizations, which may be called on to
implement many Stability Pact proposals, were kept out of the loop
until this month when 120 representatives met in Thessaloniki with
Pact envoys. Many came away with complaints with the Pact.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have no money of their own to spend,'' said James Lyon, a
Balkans economic expert with the International Crisis Group. ''They
are basically coordinating how everyone else is spending their
money and they are not even doing that well.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Stability Pact: http://www.stabilitypact.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-17-00 1252 </TRAILER>
