<BODY>
<HEADLINE> To shop, hang out or exercise free speech, it's off to the mall  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - You have the right to free speech, you have
the right to privacy at home, you have the right to watch cops on
TV read Miranda warnings to bad guys.
</P>
<P>
   And you have the right - should you wish - to hand out brochures
at a shopping mall about the endangered Australian hairy-nosed
wombat. Or to cajole passers-by into signing your petition to run
for U.S. Senate as a Green Party candidate.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is true, but civil freedoms inside malls exist with
limits.
</P>
<P>
   Mall owners can impose rules on your free speech by specifying
where and when you can set up a table, and how much you have to pay
in advance for liability insurance in case you have a tendency to
incite riots or in case your wombat mascot has a habit of biting.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Mayer, a prominent Princeton activist currently running as
a Green Party candidate in the 12th Congressional District, said
mall rights are a major issue to minor parties and activists.
</P>
<P>
   ''I stood outside to distribute leaflets outside the Freehold
Raceway Mall (in 1992). The security folks asked me to leave. I
said I had a constitutional right to be there. They were not
pleased to hear that,'' Mayer said. ''They brought me to the
office.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayer said established political parties do not engage in mall
pamphleteering because they have other options, such as mailings,
TV commercials, paid public events and costly fund-raisers.
Republicans can stage a media event, as they plan to Monday on the
Statehouse steps to promote their candidates for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''They do not, by and large, talk to people like we do,'' Mayer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday, the New Jersey Supreme Court released a landmark
ruling to permit activist organizations like the Green Party to
conduct petition drives and voter registration efforts in malls -
in this case Mill Creek Mall in Secaucus - free of prohibitive
insurance fees.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling reinforced a 1994 state Supreme Court opinion in a
case in which anti-war activists were barred from the Short Hills
Mall. Chief Justice Robert Wilentz declared malls had replaced the
town square and so must accept the assortment of town criers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although the ultimate purpose of these shopping centers is
commercial, their normal use is all-embracing, almost without
limit, projecting a community image,'' Wilentz wrote. ''For the
ordinary citizen it is not just an invitation to shop, but to do
whatever one would do downtown, including doing very little of
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Some people will not like it, any more perhaps than they liked
free speech at the downtown business districts. Dislike for free
speech, however, has never been the determinant of its protection
or its benefit,'' Wilentz wrote.
</P>
<P>
   As impressive as the 1994 ruling might have been to fans, it was
not bedrock. The Short Hills mall case was ruled by a minimal 4-3
majority, and of those four justices two were gone.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two still on the court, Justice Daniel O'Hern wrote the
opinion this time. But O'Hern, who now has retired also, achieved
what Wilentz could not: a 7-0 vote that will not be overturned
easily.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most businesses in the state are conducted in facilities
surrounded by parking lots far from the public streets,'' O'Hern
reiterated. ''Leafletting in heavily visited shopping areas
therefore has a very high value in our system of political
discourse. Putting too high a price on the exercise of that freedom
may destroy it.''
</P>
<P>
   There has always been a strong argument against free speech at
the mall. In the three-vote dissenting opinion written by former
Justice Marie Garibaldi in 1994, she said a mall is a big store, a
commercial property whose owners have no more First Amendment
obligation to accommodate political activists than a crowded Wawa.
</P>
<P>
   Garibaldi in her dissent said most Supreme Courts, including the
U.S. Supreme Court, saw the issue her way, which was and remains
true.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. Supreme Court also said states can handle these
questions for themselves according to their laws and local
circumstances. New Jersey residents are perhaps unique in the
nation in their dependence on a network of shopping malls.
</P>
<P>
   Most shopping malls accepted the 1994 ruling and made reasonable
rules for people like Mayer and his friends. ''It was Mill Creek
that decided to be really hard nosed about it,'' said Frank Askin,
a Rutgers University law professor who argued both mall cases on
behalf of the American Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than coping with a vulnerable, divided ruling from six
years ago, the owners of the Mill Creek Mall now have a unanimous
ruling with little room for ambiguity.
</P>
<P>
   James Hirschhorn, a lawyer for a national association of malls,
said the O'Hern ruling dealt not with basic mall rights but with
the details, and it set a reasonable balance.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, activists with a track record of causing
disruptions or provoking hostility can be forced to pay for high
insurance coverage. O'Hern merely said mall owners cannot assume
the worst, but must document a basis for their fears. ''The
business owner has got to have facts,'' Hirschhorn said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-17-00 1252 </TRAILER>
