<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shas Schools in Political Crisis  </HEADLINE>
By RON KAMPEAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- While most of his classmates spent recess
singing the praise of God, Yosef Kahn practiced dribbling and
dunking. Basketball is a favorite pastime, he confessed -- until one
of his friends whispered in his ear to correct him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I prefer Torah,'' the sixth-grader quickly said, referring to
the biblical studies that take up five hours of his eight-hour
schoolday.
</P>
<P>
   Kahn attends the ''Light of the Torah'' school, a soaring new
structure perched over a panorama of Jerusalem, and one of about
200 educational institutions run by the ultra-Orthodox Shas party.
</P>
<P>
   The Shas schools are at the center of a bitter political row
that is threatening to topple Prime Minister Ehud Barak's
government and bring the Middle East peace process to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   Secular Israelis say Shas is using its political clout to extort
millions of dollars in government funds for schools that
indoctrinate pupils and turn them against the democratic system
that allowed the party to flourish in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Shas leaders say the schools, which have 25,000 students,
redress decades of discrimination against religious Jews of
Sephardic, or Middle Eastern, background -- and they are prepared to
leave Barak's government if their demands are not met.
</P>
<P>
   ''This money is meant to reduce the gaps in Israeli society,''
said Shas spokesman Yitzhak Sudri. ''What the Ashkenazi (European
Jewish) establishment did for 40 years to the Sephardic population
simply brought them to depravity. They weren't educated enough,
they didn't have chances to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Shas critics say the party has controlled cash-intensive Cabinet
ministries for most of the 16 years of its existence.
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup poll published in the Maariv newspaper on Friday found
that 71 percent of secular Israelis believe Sephardic Orthodox
children are now favored by the system. The poll had a margin of
error of 4.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The clash came to a head last week when Shas ministers voted
with the opposition for new elections.
</P>
<P>
   That's usually a fireable offense. However, Barak is scrambling
to keep Shas in his Cabinet, fearful that the party's departure
would create a minority government lacking the credibility to
finalize the peace treaty with the Palestinians he has promised for
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Shas leaders are furious with Education Minister Yossi Sarid,
who has refused to transfer $7.5 million in emergency funds to the
Shas school system he says has already richly benefited from
government magnanimity.
</P>
<P>
   Sarid, who heads the secular Meretz party, says the system is
bankrupt because of mismanagement, and wants future funding closely
supervised by his ministry.
</P>
<P>
   As a way out of the crisis, Barak is considering removing the
Shas schools from Sarid's oversight. However, this would not solve
deeper tensions.
</P>
<P>
   In return for loyalty to Barak, Shas wants the government to
fund a transportation system for its students and to legalize its
five pirate radio stations. Both could be powerful tools for
mobilizing voters in future elections. Shas has grown steadily over
the years, and now is the third-largest party in parliament, with
17 of 120 legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Secular Israelis say the religious schools offer little more
than indoctrination. They say Shas helps perpetuate poverty -- and
creates new Shas voters dependent on handouts from the party --
because students don't learn what is necessary to compete in a
modern world.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's creating an enclave,'' said A.B. Yehoshua, a noted
Israeli writer. ''They don't study civics or subjects that will
prepare them for professions.''
</P>
<P>
   Shas educators counter that religious study does not impede
integration into Israeli society; in fact, they say, the gargantuan
memory and interpretive skills required to master the Talmud, the
vast commentary on Jewish law, are enough to ground the students in
any pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   ''Kids who have studied Talmud learn quickly,'' said Rabbi
Shlomo Bresca, the principal of Light of the Torah, claiming that
an increasing number of ultra-Orthodox are joining Israel's
burgeoning high-tech work force.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, Shas says, the schools provide the children
with a moral basis to survive modern decadence.
</P>
<P>
   Bresca is quick to point out that it is only the boys' school
that has benefited from the recent cash flow. Down the street, the
girls still study 30 to a class in cramped metal shacks that burn
in midday summer heat. Both schools have about 265 pupils each.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the dedication of the teachers, who work long hours at
low pay,'' that make Shas schools attractive, he said. ''Secular
teachers walk out over not getting a 10 percent raise. Our teachers
have waited months for salaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the teachers appear to have answered a calling. At
the boys' school, they enraptured pupils with energetic
explanations of religious duties.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Avraham Avergil strode among a cluster of first-graders,
reviewing how many times a day one recites the ''Shema,'' the
one-sentence encapsulation of monotheism and chosenness said to be
the essence of Jewish belief.
</P>
<P>
   ''You say it when you ... ,'' he bellowed, and then dropped his
cheek into the palm of his hand. ''Go to sleep!'' the boys shouted.
''And when you...,'' he stretched. ''Wake up!'' they shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Still, secular concepts have a way of creeping into even this
insular society. The sixth-grade girls -- who study a much greater
proportion of the state-set curriculum -- were asked to write essays
on what system of government they preferred. Each chose the
republican system, explaining that an elected government better
guaranteed their rights.
</P>
<P>
   The boys spend much more time studying religion -- but they too
are not invulnerable to secular customs. Yosef Kahn, the hoop
dreamer, could not remember where he learned his basketball moves.
It wasn't in school -- no gym class -- nor at home, where TV is
banned.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, he remembered: ''On the street.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
