<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton goes on the attack to ''define'' Lazio  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - In what one veteran New York Democratic
strategist calls a ''very perilous strategy,'' Hillary Rodham
Clinton is directly attacking her new Senate rival, Rep. Rick
Lazio, in campaign appearances and television advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy was on display Tuesday when she visited a hospital
in suburban Westchester County. She said Lazio's positions were out
of step with most New Yorkers and that he too often flip-flopped on
important issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're going to have a great time trying to find out where he
stands on issues,'' she said. ''If you look at his record, it sort
of depends on who's the last person he talked to.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the first lady stepped things up with a half-hour
speech to 1,100 women supporters in New York City, calling the Long
Island congressman ''a follower, not a leader'' and accusing him of
voting ''against the interests of New York women, children and
families.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little disagreement as to why the first lady has gone
on the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ''She is under intense pressure, based upon the polls, to define
him quickly and to reduce her negatives ... She will begin to
define him before he gets on television in a major way and defines
himself,'' said Democratic strategist Hank Sheinkopf.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran of President Clinton's 1996 re-election campaign, the
New York-based Sheinkopf is not involved in the U.S. Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, not well known outside his home district in Suffolk
County, entered the Senate race on the Republican side just a month
ago after Mayor Rudolph Giuliani withdrew because of prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Four independent polls out since the switch have shown the race
is a statistical tie or extremely close, or much the same as it was
when Giuliani was running.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times/CBS News poll out Tuesday had Clinton barely
ahead of Lazio, 44 percent to 39 percent, among likely voters. It
found that three in 10 voters had an unfavorable opinion of the
first lady while 62 percent said they either didn't know enough
about Lazio to form an opinion or were undecided about him.
</P>
<P>
   New York Republicans say the new Clinton aggressiveness is a
sign of concern on the part of the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ''This obviously is a desperation move,'' said Dan McLagan, a
spokesman for Lazio's campaign. ''She spent a year introducing
herself to New Yorkers. They've met her, they've heard about her,
they don't like her ... They are turning to the tried and true
Clinton method of search and destroy.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spokesman Howard Wolfson disputed that, saying there
wasn't any real change in strategy and that the candidate and her
campaign have been spelling out differences with Lazio ever since
he entered the race. Nonetheless, Wolfson said that in the past
week Clinton had pulled the individual elements of the criticism
together.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to talk about the issue differences. They're
significant,'' Wolfson said.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, Clinton is seeking to portray Lazio as too
conservative for New York and a sidekick of former House Speaker
Newt Gingrich. Lazio says he is a moderate Republican in tune with
mainstream New York voters.
</P>
<P>
   Sheinkopf said Thursday that he expected Clinton to quickly
press her effort with new television ads attacking the
congressman's voting record while praising her own work as first
lady and before.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, on Friday, Clinton launched two new television ads
attacking Lazio for not supporting the Patients' Bill of Rights
legislation and for not being an active supporter of hate crimes
legislation sought by gay rights activists. Both ads end with the
tag line: ''The more you know, the more you wonder.'' They were the
first TV ads of the campaign in which one candidate directly
attacked the other.
</P>
<P>
   But Sheinkopf cautioned that Clinton is engaging in ''a very
perilous strategy to some extent. It could backfire and increase
her own negatives.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio camp believes that may happen if it plays its cards
right. To help counter her attacks, the Lazio campaign is stepping
up positive TV spots touting the congressman as a family man who
has spent his life in New York.
</P>
<P>
   And Lazio has sought to reinforce the notion that Clinton is
going negative.
</P>
<P>
   ''New Yorkers deserve a clean campaign on the issues. Mrs.
Clinton's mudslinging is an affront to them,'' he said after her
Wednesday attack. ''New Yorkers deserve much better than Mrs.
Clinton offered today.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Clinton strategy may carry risks, the first lady's
advisers feel she has a cushion and point to the Times/CBS poll as
evidence of that. The poll found that 74 percent of voters felt she
was spending more time discussing issues than attacking Lazio. Only
nine percent saw things the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the numbers, Sheinkopf said Clinton doesn't have much
choice.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's in a very difficult position,'' he said. ''She's got to
define him faster than he defines himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Marc Humbert has covered New York politics for The Associated
Press for more than 20 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-17-00 1341 </TRAILER>
