<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Grandparents Seek Trinidad Boy  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SCHUSLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   TACARIGUA, Trinidad (AP) -- The case has all the makings of the
Elian Gonzalez custody battle -- a motherless boy, a blue-collar dad
and feuding relatives -- but this time the father is a convicted
felon fighting to keep his 6-year-old on this Caribbean island.
</P>
<P>
   The core question is whether the rights of the boy's father,
Anthony Alvarez, overrule a standing custody order and the
opportunities that the boy might enjoy in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just want to stay with my dad,'' said Brandon, whose fair
skin makes him stand out in a country mostly divided between
descendants of Africans and East Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing content in the quiet hamlet in north-central Trinidad,
Brandon -- for the time being -- lives with his dad and cousins in a
modest, one-story home full of puppets, Nintendo video games, and
cousins. His father, who once earned $400 a week as a landscape
contractor in the United States, now makes $40 a week bagging rice.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez was deported to his native Trinidad in 1998. In
February, a district court granted sole custody to maternal
grandparents Robert and Kathleen Willard of Nashua, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Much like the Elian Gonzalez case, Brandon's tale began with a
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 2, 1996, Brandon's mother, Lara, was killed in a car
crash in Massachusetts en route to classes at Fitchburg State
College. She was 20, months from a nursing degree and planning to
wed Alvarez, with whom she lived together with Brandon.
</P>
<P>
   That year Alvarez served four months of a felony conviction
stemming from a mugging in Nashua. The judge commuted the sentence
when he was told of the mother's death.
</P>
<P>
   The boy and his father were reunited for a short time, but in
May 1998 Alvarez was detained and deported because of his felony
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Both grandparents were given joint custody and Brandon spent
weekdays with paternal grandmother Joy Alvarez and weekends with
the Willards. Both live in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The climax came when the Willards tried to prevent Brandon's
visit to Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't want him to go on this trip because he was going to
miss too much school,'' said Mr. Willard, 58. The dispute led to
their successful motion for sole custody.
</P>
<P>
   But two days later, Joy Alvarez took the boy to Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   Now jailed in Manchester, N.H., she is unable to pay her
$500,000 bond and faces up to seven years imprisonment for
interfering with the custody order.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have been telling the Willards for the longest time that the
best thing for Brandon is to be with me -- yet I know that the best
opportunities for him are in the United States,'' Alvarez said. He
said he is willing to allow visitation rights, but doesn't feel
they'll compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The Willards visited Trinidad in April and gave the U.S. embassy
court papers establishing their custody and tried to persuade the
father to give up his son.
</P>
<P>
   So far they've had no response, Robert Willard said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We continue to try to work cooperatively with Tony, which we
see as being best for everybody, especially Brandon,'' Willard
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that going to court in Trinidad was an option they have
not yet considered and are reluctant to pursue.
</P>
<P>
   But Christopher Lamora, public affairs officer at the State
Department's Office of Children's Issues, noted that Trinidad was
not a signatory to the Hague Convention on the Civil Aspects of
International Child Abduction, which would normally apply in such
cases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-17-00 1430 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000617.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assad May Allow Domestic Change  </HEADLINE>
By HAMZA HENDAWI
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- In a series of interviews as his father
groomed him for the Syrian presidency, Bashar Assad offered a
glimpse of his thinking and gave the world a chance to get to know
him. He has stuck close to his father's line on peace with Israel,
but shown himself more open to domestic change.
</P>
<P>
   Now that his father is gone -- Hafez Assad died June 10 of a
heart attack after 30 years in power -- Bashar Assad has said very
little in public. On Saturday, he declined to speak to reporters
covering a meeting of Syria's ruling Baath Party.
</P>
<P>
   During his father's funeral Tuesday, Bashar Assad praised
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright for having a good grasp of
Syria's realities. ''That is very good news for our country and
people to hear that you understand,'' he said through an
interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in Syria ''is committed to continue in the same way
that President Assad was following,'' he told Albright. This last
remark was taken to mean that Bashar Assad, 34 years old and a
political novice, would stick to his father's uncompromising
approach in peace talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Egyptian weekly Al-Osboa, conducted two
weeks before Assad died but published last Monday, Bashar said: ''I
would like to stress that peace to Syria is a strategic choice.
When Syria took part in the (1991) Madrid (peace) conference, and
then in the peace talks with Israel, it went with fixed principles
that could not be divided or partitioned.''
</P>
<P>
   Bashar outlined the principles as: Not a single inch of land to
remain under Israeli control, and Syria wants full control over the
northeastern shore of the Sea of Galilee.
</P>
<P>
   He appears to be prepared to permit a higher level of pluralism
and freedom of expression than his father. But, in the same
Al-Osboa interview, he fell short of endorsing a full-fledged
democratic system.
</P>
<P>
   The young Assad's career as an eye doctor in a west London
hospital ended when his elder brother Basil, his father's first
choice for a successor, died in a 1994 car accident.
</P>
<P>
   But he has lived almost his entire life in Syria, where his
father ruled with an iron grip and showed zero tolerance for
dissent. Under Hafez Assad, Syria endured long spells as an
isolated, or even pariah, nation because of western allegations
that it sponsored terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe in democracy and I respect others' opinions to a
large extent. ... I believe that it is necessary to listen to the
point of views of all the others whatever different and
contradictory,'' Bashar Assad told Al-Osboa. ''There is no harm to
Syria if we have a strong and active media that opens the door for
everyone far away from a single opinion or a single point of
view.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
