<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee shop changes name, again, to satisfy Federal Express  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - A coffee shop has changed its name a third
time to satisfy shipping giant Federal Express' copyright
infringement claims.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly known as Federal Espresso, then Ex-Federal Espresso,
the owners have ironically named their java business ''Freedom of
Espresso.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Memphis, Tenn.,-based FedEx filed a copyright
infringement lawsuit against the coffee bar's owners in U.S.
District Court in Syracuse. It was settled recently, Syracuse
Newspapers reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''All we had to do was buy an 'O' and an 'M,''' to create a sign
with the new name on it, said co-owner Anna Dobbs.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that was not quite the sum of what changed.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs' brother and business partner, David Ruston, said he has
at least 200 pounds of stationery at his home sitting next to the
fireplace, ready to burn. It all carried the contentious name.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the Syracuse shops owned by Dobbs and Ruston, the only
reference to the old name is outside the building. Beneath a sign
bearing the new name is another that reads, ''Formerly known as
Ex-Federal Espresso.'' Under the settlement agreement, the shop can
keep that sign up for 60 days, said the shop's lawyer, Joseph
Heath.
</P>
<P>
   Dobbs and Ruston are bound by the settlement not to discuss the
terms.
</P>
<P>
   A FedEx lawyer also would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year legal battle did not appear to kill business for
the store. Dobbs and Ruston plan to open a third shop soon. Which
means Heath will have a new place to collect legal fees - he
charged one cup of coffee a day indefinitely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
