<DOCNO> APW20000617.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> With AP Photo  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY McSHANE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Standing before a media horde at his first
Manhattan news conference last month, incoming Archbishop Edward
Egan acknowledged something wasn't quite right.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't feel like the boss,'' he confessed. ''But give me a
little time and I will.''
</P>
<P>
   Five weeks later, the time is now for the 68-year-old Egan. On
Sunday, in a St. Patrick's Cathedral ceremony, he officially
becomes the 12th head of the sprawling Archdiocese of New York and
its 2.4 million members.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, an elaborate installation Mass complete with a
45-minute procession of 700 priests will mark the conservative
Catholic prelate's ascent to the St. Patrick's pulpit. There, he
will address a crowd of about 3,000 invited guests.
</P>
<P>
   The attendees are a mix of the sacred and the secular: eight
cardinals will join first lady Hillary Clinton, U.S. Rep. Rick
Lazio, Supreme Court justices Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas,
Gov. George Pataki, U.S. Sen. Charles Schumer and Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Egan is swapping suburban Connecticut for a Manhattan fishbowl,
moving into the official residence on Madison Avenue. He instantly
becomes America's most visible Catholic; his Sunday sermons will
soon become fodder for tabloid headlines.
</P>
<P>
   But the former bishop of Bridgeport wasn't talking about his new
job, putting off interviews until he put in a full week on the job.
He first wants to meet people and get a feel for the diocese and
its 413 parishes.
</P>
<P>
   ''He wants to familiarize himself as to where things stand now
in the archdiocese,'' said spokesman Joe Zwilling. There's plenty
to learn: New York is the nation's third-largest archdiocese,
behind Los Angeles and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Egan has yet to even set his regular schedule for celebrating
Mass in the cathedral, Zwilling said.
</P>
<P>
   But some things are already known about Egan: he is a firm
believer in church doctrine, unwavering in his opposition to
abortion and birth control.
</P>
<P>
   Egan was born in Oak Park, Ill., the hometown of Ernest
Hemingway. He graduated from Rome's prestigious Gregorian
Pontifical University in 1958. Ordained in Rome, he spent the next
two decades in Chicago or the Vatican in several positions.
</P>
<P>
   Egan became a bishop in 1985, and spent the next three years
working with his predecessor, Cardinal John O'Connor, as vicar for
education in the archdiocese of New York.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988 he became bishop in Bridgeport, where he was hailed for
reorganizing diocesan schools, recruiting local men into the
priesthood, and fund-raising. But during his tenure, the diocese
was forced to defend itself against more than two dozen lawsuits
about alleged sexual molestation by local priests.
</P>
<P>
   Though all but one of the cases predated Egan's arrival, the
incidents raised embarrassing questions about whether the abuse was
covered up.
</P>
<P>
   Egan was named May 11 to replace O'Connor, who had died of
cancer eight days earlier after 16 years on the job. O'Connor will
be remembered in prayers at both ceremonies for Egan.
</P>
<P>
   The new archbishop assumes his duties Sunday before an afternoon
prayer service.
</P>
<P>
   Egan will first bless the congregation with holy water before
his papal letter of appointment is read and notarized in the
cathedral's sanctuary. At that point, he officially becomes
archbishop.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Egan will celebrate the Mass of installation and
deliver the homily.
</P>
<P>
   The new archbishop's namesake nephew, Edward Michael Egan, will
present the gifts for communion. The archbishop selected some music
for the Mass; a friend, opera star Renee Fleming, will perform
''Alleluia'' from Mozart's ''Exultate Jubilate.''
</P>
<P>
   In his farewell news conference at Bridgeport, Egan said one of
his major objectives in New York was bringing in more priests and
other religious vocations. In his first Mass at St. Patrick's, Egan
installed five new priests.
</P>
<P>
   All five will attend the Sunday service with Egan.
</P>
<P>
   He must also deal with the archdiocese's school system - 238
elementary schools and 55 high schools with 113,000 students. Egan
has said he hopes to keep all the schools open.
</P>
<P>
   A bit of unfinished business remains in Bridgeport, Conn. - on
June 27, he will return to ordain a group of permanent deacons
there. Two days later, he will be in Rome to receive the blessing
of Pope John Paul II in his new job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
