<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin in Moldova for Gas Debt Talk  </HEADLINE>
By ALISON MUTLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHISINAU, Moldova (AP) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin
promised Saturday to help Moldova resolve a dispute over a
breakaway, Russian-speaking enclave and affirmed his support for
the territorial integrity of this impoverished former Soviet
republic.
</P>
<P>
   Resolving the Trans-Dniester region's problems would help Moscow
comply with a promise made last year by former President Boris
Yeltsin to remove the 2,500 Russian troops and equipment still
stationed on Moldovan territory by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian and Ukrainian-speaking populations of Trans-Dniester
declared independence in 1990, fearing that the Romanian-speaking
leadership of the newly independent country would reunite with
neighboring Romania.
</P>
<P>
   A war erupted from 1991 to 1992 in which some 1,500 people died.
Russian troops stationed in Moldova since Soviet times intervened
in 1992 to end the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Putin announced at a news conference that had appointed former
Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov to head a ''settlement commission''
to help resolve the status of Trans-Dniester. Primakov was the
author of a 1997 memorandum which Moscow hopes will be the basis of
a settlement between Trans-Dniester and the Moldovan government.
</P>
<P>
   ''The national interests of Russia are that Moldova should be
self-sufficient, territorially integral and independent,'' Putin
told reporters before departing for Moscow at the end of a 15-hour
visit.
</P>
<P>
   Trans-Dniester, which borders Ukraine, comprises one-tenth of
Moldova's total land area and has an estimated population of
600,000.
</P>
<P>
   According to Moldovan sources, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, Putin turned down a request by the leader of
Trans-Dniester separatists, Igor Smirnov, for a private meeting in
Chisinau.
</P>
<P>
   That was a clear signal to the separatists that Moscow expects
them to resolve their differences with Moldovan President Petru
Lucinschi short of their goal of independence.
</P>
<P>
   During his news conference, Putin did not mention the withdrawal
agreement, which Yeltsin accepted during last year's summit of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe in Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   The OSCE has expressed concern that although the deadline is
still nearly two years away, the Russians have announced no
timetable for the withdrawal. Trans-Dniester separatists oppose the
withdrawal because they consider the Russian troops their
protectors.
</P>
<P>
   Some diplomats were concerned that Putin, who was elected
president on the promise to restore Russia's role in the world,
might be reluctant to remove Russian forces from a strategic area
against the wishes of the local Russian-speaking population.
</P>
<P>
   Trans-Dniester has developed into a major smuggling center for
weapons and other supplies, depriving both Moldova and neighboring
Ukraine of customs revenues and presenting a threat to regional
security.
</P>
<P>
   ''During the negotiations, Putin said he does not intend to keep
Moldova on a short leash, including by using Russian troops,''
Lucinschi said.
</P>
<P>
   Less progress was evident, however, on the other major issue
between Russia and Moldova -- the country's $861 million debt to
Moscow for natural gas. Moldova's economy virtually collapsed after
the Russian currency crisis of 1998 undermined the principal market
for Moldovan exports, mostly wine and agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
   A Moldovan spokesman said Putin and Lucinschi discussed the debt
issue into the early hours of Saturday, but there was no
announcement of any breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot go to the Russians with an outstretched hand, but
Russians cannot give aid without knowing they will be paid back,''
Lucinschi at the news conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-17-00 1445 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000617.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Council Discusses Backing Pullout  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- With Lebanon still insisting that Israel
occupies part of its territory, the U.N. Security Council met
Saturday to discuss endorsing Secretary-General Kofi Annan's
announcement that Israel has completely withdrawn from southern
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   A day after he first rejected the U.N. verification of Israel's
pullout, Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss said Saturday that
Lebanon is committed to cooperating with the United Nations. But he
reiterated that the country ''insists on recovering every inch of
its territory.''
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations had long planned to move in after an Israeli
pullout from southern Lebanon and verify that Israel had completely
left Lebanese soil. Before heading to the Middle East on Friday,
Annan announced that the world body had completed the verification
process.
</P>
<P>
   But Hoss quickly responded, saying Lebanese officers working
with the U.N. team inspecting the border had found several Israeli
military outposts inside Lebanon. His rejection of the U.N.
announcement was a setback for Annan, who had hoped to discuss the
next steps to achieve peace in the Middle East during his trip to
the region.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the controversy will likely dominate Annan's meetings
in Beirut on Monday with top Lebanese officials.
</P>
<P>
   Israel invaded Lebanon in 1978 and occupied part of southern
Lebanon as a buffer against guerrilla attacks on northern Israel
from 1985 until its withdrawal on May 24. Under the 1978 Security
Council resolutions, U.N. peacekeeping troops were to help the
Lebanese army restore security and authority in the border zone
after U.N. workers verified Israel's departure.
</P>
<P>
   But the dispute over Israel's withdrawal has delayed the
deployment of the peacekeeping troops -- and more critically the
deployment of the Lebanese army to the region. The Lebanese army's
presence is important because since the Israeli pullout, Shiite
Muslim Hezbollah guerrillas who fought the Israeli troops for years
have moved into the former occupied zone and taken de facto
control.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrilla presence in the zone right across from Israel's
border is especially a concern for residents of northern Israeli
towns, who fear guerrilla attacks. On Saturday, Hezbollah warned it
will resume attacks on Israel's north if the Jewish state does not
give up tracts of land claimed by Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ''All violations should be dealt with; ... otherwise we consider
the mission of liberating Lebanese territory to be incomplete and
resistance remains our choice to liberate the last inch of our
occupied land,'' Hezbollah said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The draft statement being debated by the Security Council calls
on the Lebanese government ''to ensure the return of its effective
authority and to maximize its presence in the south.'' It welcomes
measures taken by the secretary-general to beef up the 4,500-strong
U.N. peacekeeping force in Lebanon, but it stresses that U.N.
redeployment to the border ''shall be carried out in coordination
with the redeployment of the Lebanese armed forces.''
</P>
<P>
   A Security Council endorsement of Israel's withdrawal would put
its political weight behind the U.N. position, rather than
Lebanon's. That could pose difficulties for some council members,
particularly Russia. Moscow has close ties to Syria, the main power
broker in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Timur Goksel, spokesman for the U.N. force in Lebanon, said
Saturday that no peacekeepers will be deployed before matters are
sorted out with the Lebanese government, possibly during talks
Monday with Annan.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has been said all along that Lebanese consent is a
prerequisite of U.N. deployment in any place in the country,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak's office welcomed Annan's declaration,
saying in a statement Saturday that it now expects the United
Nations to act to ''help restore law and order in the area.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-17-00 1502 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000617.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court critical of Congress as it overturns conviction based on overseas crime </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Blaming inaction by Congress for forcing its
hand, a federal appeals court has reversed the sex-abuse conviction
of a man who fathered a child with his 13-year-old stepdaughter at
a U.S. military base in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling made public Friday, the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals said U.S. courts did not have jurisdiction over a case set
outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   However, the court said it reached that conclusion ''with
regret,'' and noted it was taking the unusual step of forwarding a
copy of its opinion to the chairpersons of the House and Senate
Armed Forces and Judiciary committees so changes to laws can be
considered.
</P>
<P>
   The comments came in a written decision dated Thursday. The
appeals court said the U.S. District Court in Brooklyn was not the
appropriate venue to bring charges against a civilian who committed
a crime in Germany. It then dismissed the indictment against the
defendant, Milton Gatlin.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling reversed his guilty plea in Brooklyn to a charge of
sexually abusing a minor. A message left with his lawyer for
comment was not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   Gatlin was charged with a crime which prosecutors allege
occurred after March 1993, when he married Gail Taylor, a U.S. Army
sergeant stationed at an Army base in Darmstadt, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court said that sometime in August 1996, while his
wife was on duty in Bosnia, Gatlin began having sexual intercourse
in Germany with a 13-year-old daughter of Taylor by a previous
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   The court said Gatlin, who was 34 years old at the time,
continued to have sexual relations with the girl regularly through
at least January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   After returning to the United States, she gave birth to a child
in September 1997, and later revealed that she had been having sex
with Gatlin, the court said. A genetic test later confirmed his
paternity.
</P>
<P>
   Gatlin was charged with engaging in sexual acts with a minor. He
pleaded guilty after a judge in Brooklyn rejected a defense request
to have the charges dismissed because the alleged crime occurred
outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On July 16, Gatlin was sentenced to four years and three months
in prison and was ordered to pay $1,000 in restitution.
</P>
<P>
   In throwing out the case against him, the 2nd Circuit said its
ruling ''should come as little surprise to anyone familiar with the
history of criminal prosecution of civilians accompanying the
military overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   Supreme Court rulings as far back as 1957 have found that
civilians accompanying the military overseas cannot be prosecuted
in the United States, the court said. But each time, critics,
including government commissions and independent scholars, demanded
that Congress change laws to allow the prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the court noted, Congress thus far has not ''responded to
this call for legislation, though its inaction hardly can be blamed
on a lack of awareness of the gap. Indeed, Congress has held
several hearings on the matter, and, over the last four decades,
has entertained more than 30 bills aimed at closing the gap.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the court acknowledged that Congress has passed laws
allowing the prosecution of certain crimes such as terrorism when
they occur outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In one footnote, the 2nd Circuit referenced an earlier case in
the United States in which charges against two women were dropped
even though evidence showed they had brutally killed their
husbands, both American soldiers, while the families were stationed
on military bases overseas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-17-00 1504 </TRAILER>
