<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Navy Detains 56 Protesters in Range  </HEADLINE>
By ISMAEL TORRES
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Navy officers detained 56
demonstrators Saturday who had invaded the U.S. military bombing
range on Vieques to demand the Navy leave the small Caribbean
island.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 56 people arrested, 19 were released on Vieques after
being cited to appear in federal court on trespassing charges, Navy
spokesman Robert Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   The 37 others were taken to the naval base on the main island of
Puerto Rico, where four were cited and released, and 33 remained in
custody because they were ''not being cooperative,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're not giving the information necessary to cite them,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Navy lawyers were talking with ''all the appropriate people,''
including federal magistrates, to decide how to proceed with the
33. A court date has not been set for those cited, but they could
appear in court as early as Monday, Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Among those arrested were 20 doctors -- from surgeons to general
practitioners -- who said in a statement: ''We are a group
representing Puerto Rican doctors who are concerned about the
health and future of the people of Vieques.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said he didn't know if the doctors were among those
detained at the base.
</P>
<P>
   Decades of resentment over the Navy's presence on Vieques boiled
over in April 1999, when a jet dropped two 500-pound bombs
off-target and killed a civilian security guard. It was the first
fatality in 60 years since the Navy took over two-thirds of the
20-mile-long island, dislodging thousands of residents. Some 9,300
civilians now live there.
</P>
<P>
   People's anger was compounded when the Navy admitted it had
illegally and accidentally fired 263 armor-piercing bullets tipped
with depleted uranium on the range in February 1999, and Puerto
Rican officials said they were never informed.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of protesters occupied the range for a year to prevent
more bombing. They were forced out in a federal operation May 4,
and the Navy resumed training under a deal that calls for a
referendum before February 2002 and the use of inert ordnance until
after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   If the Navy loses the vote, it would have to leave the island by
May 2003, giving up a site it says is crucial for the kind of
realistic training that saves lives in combat.
</P>
<P>
   But many Vieques residents accuse the Navy of contaminating
their environment, destroying fishing grounds and coral reefs,
keeping away tourists, and contributing to a 14 percent
unemployment rate. Dozens are filing lawsuits claiming their health
problems, from respiratory illnesses to cancers, are related to the
military exercises.
</P>
<P>
   New York-based environmental lawyer Robert F. Kennedy Jr. was
leading a group of scientists Saturday to test the island's soil
and water to support a separate suit against the U.S. government
over environmental and human rights issues in Vieques.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
