<HEADLINE> Iranian Publisher Imprisoned  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- An Iranian publisher has been imprisoned for
insulting Iran's supreme leader, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, during the
February election campaign, newspapers reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Alireza Khoshandam, who runs a small book-publishing house
called Creative Dialogue Publications, was prosecuted for remarks
made during his unsuccessful bid to gain election to parliament.
</P>
<P>
   A hard-line Revolutionary Court sentenced Khoshandam to prison
on Thursday, the reformist Hayat-e-Nou reported. His sentence was
not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The charges against him include insulting . . . the Supreme
Leader in his election campaign speeches,'' the paper said.
Insulting Khamenei or questioning his absolute power is a
punishable offense in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear why Khoshandam was only sent to prison now. No
other details were available.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-liners in the judiciary opposed to the reforms of President
Mohammad Khatami have ordered the arrest of several journalists and
the closure of 19 publications since April.
</P>
<P>
   A press bill being drafted in parliament seeks to prohibit the
Special Clergy Court and the Revolutionary Court from taking any
action against journalists. In the Feb. 18 elections, reformists
won a majority in parliament for the first time since the 1979
Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would prohibit the arbitrary closure of a newspaper
without judicial process. It would also ban no-jury trials for
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   The media has been at the forefront of the Khatami-led campaign
for political and social reform.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-liners say the reforms violate Islamic principles.
</P>
</TEXT>
