<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio: Missed vote just part of the campaign  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN Jr.
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKDALE, N.Y. (AP) - Two days after missing a Congressional
vote, U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio said Saturday that he will remain in the
House while campaigning and trust that New York voters will
understand when there are conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am not considering stepping down,'' Lazio told reporters at
a ceremony honoring veterans of the Normandy invasion. ''I think
it's a matter of duty ... We're staying in.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, the Republican candidate for U.S. Senate, missed
Thursday's vote on a $10 million funding bill that would have
established a 2 million barrel home heating oil reserve. Lazio
supported the bill, which was voted down in the House, 195-193.
</P>
<P>
   The four-term Congressman was flying back to New York, where he
had a full day of campaigning on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to miss some votes, because I need to get around
the state,'' said Lazio, who boasted a 99 percent attendance record
in Congress. ''We got into this race very late. It's the nature of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Long Island Republican said he believed New York voters
would understand when he was absent from Washington because of the
campaign: ''I think people understood it when (Democrat) Chuck
Schumer ran for the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio also used the opportunity to take a shot at his Democratic
opponent, first lady Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''My opponent has yet to cast a single legislative vote, so I'm
really proud of my attendance record,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Clinton unveiled two new television ads that
questioned Lazio's voting record. ''Rick Lazio: The more you know
... the more you wonder,'' the ads said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the ads, Lazio said Clinton had embraced ''negative
campaigning and distortions. ... They would like me to slip down to
that level, to get down in the mud where they are now, but I'm not
going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, a Clinton spokesman, said there wasn't any real
change in strategy and that the candidate and her campaign have
been spelling out differences with Lazio ever since he entered the
race.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to talk about the issue differences. They're
significant,'' Wolfson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
