<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sunbathers to be booted from Higbee Beach to restore bird habitat  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOWER TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) - Sunbathers - clothed and nude alike
- will be banned from a portion of Higbee Beach beginning next
summer, in an effort to give terns, gulls and other shore birds a
safe place to nest and feed.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the state Division of Fish and Wildlife to make
the 1,000-foot stretch of sand off-limits comes a year after nude
sunbathers were forbidden at the Cape May County beach.
</P>
<P>
   State officials have said they want to see if shore birds will
return to the area if they are protected from human interference.
</P>
<P>
   ''If keeping human beings out of there doesn't bring the birds
back, the area will be opened up again in a year or two,'' Jo Ann
Cubberly, the head of the state Bureau of Tidelands Management,
told The Star-Ledger of Newark for Saturday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year ban, which will stretch from May 1 to Sept. 15,
will not begin until next summer. Other parts of Higbee will remain
open.
</P>
<P>
   Higbee Beach's popularity with nude sunbathers came to an end
last year when Gov. Christie Whitman signed a bill enabling local
governments to control behavior on state property. The beach, part
of a 1,000-acre wildlife management area, is one of only a few
maritime forests remaining at the shore.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to curb lewd behavior that had been reported in
the area, Lower Township passed an ordinance banning nude
sunbathing in 1988. But part of the beach is located on federal
land, and a Cape May Court House couple fought the state law and
local ordinance on the grounds that the township had no right to
regulate federal property.
</P>
<P>
   The state Legislature has approved a bill - now awaiting
Whitman's signature - to close that loophole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-17-00 1601 </TRAILER>
