<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian P.M. Resignation Expected  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- Jordan's prime minister is expected to
tender his government's resignation Sunday, clearing the way for
King Abdullah II to appoint a replacement, government officials
said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Reports emerged Thursday that a Cabinet reshuffle was imminent,
but there has been no official word on why Prime Minister
Abdur-Ra'uf S. Rawabdeh is to step down. In April, though, a group
of legislators urged Abdullah to dismiss the government, accusing
it of failing to deliver on political and economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Rawabdeh, the first prime minister to serve under Abdullah since
he ascended the throne in February 1999, is seen as conservative.
Abdullah is believed to be impatient for reform.
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah is likely to ask Ali Abu Ragheb, a senior economist and
former trade and industry minister, to form a new Cabinet,
government officials said. They spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Ragheb, who studied in the United States, heads the
parliament's economic committee and is a member of an economic
consultative council chaired by Abdullah. He is known to advocate
liberal economic reform and the privatization of profitable state
firms.
</P>
<P>
   The king has often consulted Abu Ragheb on economic policy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
