<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Navy Detains 56 Vieques Protesters  </HEADLINE>
By ISMAEL TORRES
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Navy officers detained 56
demonstrators Saturday after they invaded the U.S. Navy bombing
range on Vieques island and demanded that the Navy leave.
</P>
<P>
   Among those detained on the small Puerto Rican island were 20
doctors -- from surgeons to general practitioners -- who said in a
statement: ''We are a group representing Puerto Rican doctors who
are concerned about the health and future of the people of
Vieques.''
</P>
<P>
   All the protesters were cited to appear in federal court to be
charged with trespassing, Navy spokesman Robert Nelson said. They
were subsequently released. Nelson said he did not know when they
will appear in court.
</P>
<P>
   Decades of resentment over the Navy's presence on Vieques boiled
over in April 1999, when a jet dropped two 500-pound bombs
off-target and killed a civilian security guard. It was the first
fatality in 60 years since the Navy took over two-thirds of the
20-mile-long island, dislodging thousands of residents and using
part of the island as a practice bombing range. Some 9,300
civilians now live on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   People's anger was compounded when the Navy admitted it had
illegally and accidentally fired 263 armor-piercing bullets tipped
with depleted uranium on the range in February 1999. Puerto Rican
officials said they were never informed.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of protesters occupied the range for a year to prevent
more bombing. They were forced out in a federal raid May 4, and the
Navy resumed training under a deal that calls for a referendum
before February 2002 and the use of non-exploding practice bombs
until after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   If the Navy loses the referendum, it would have to leave the
island by May 2003, giving up a site it says is crucial for the
kind of realistic training that saves lives in combat.
</P>
<P>
   But many Vieques residents accuse the Navy of contaminating
their environment, destroying fishing grounds and coral reefs,
keeping away tourists and contributing to a 14 percent unemployment
rate. Dozens are filing lawsuits claiming their health problems,
from respiratory illnesses to cancers, are related to the military
exercises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-17-00 1623 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000617.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Serb Opposition Leader Healing  </HEADLINE>
By ALEN MLATISUMA
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serbia's best-known opposition
leader said Saturday he will remain in Montenegro while recovering
from a gun attack he claims was organized by President Slobodan
Milosevic's government.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegrin police said they had arrested those responsible for
the attack on Vuk Draskovic, who was slightly wounded when gunmen
fired into his vacation home at about midnight Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Police refused to give more details or say how many suspects
were in custody. But Montenegrin Deputy Interior Minister Vuk
Boskovic said the attackers had ''followed Draskovic all the way
from Serbia with a murderous intention.''
</P>
<P>
   Montenegrin authorities had promised a fuller statement
Saturday, but gave none. They also did not provide any evidence to
support the claim that the assailants had come from Serbia --
Milosevic's stronghold and the larger of the two Yugoslav
republics.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is quite clear that those who ordered (the attack) are in
Belgrade,'' Boskovic told the Montenegrin newspaper Vijesti. He
said police found the apartment where the assailants had planned
the attack, together with ''weapons and gloves'' used in the
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic said he did not know how long he would stay in
Montenegro, where the pro-Western government opposes Milosevic.
Draskovic, head of the Serbian Renewal Movement, said he had
decided to stay for ''medical assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   He told reporters Friday that orders for ''my liquidation could
not have been reached without the knowledge of those who run the
country. And in this case, it is Slobodan Milosevic and his wife.''
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, Yugoslav Telecommunications Minister Ivan Markovic
ridiculed the allegations of government involvement, saying
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Montenegrin President Milo
Djukanovic and ''terrorists'' from a militant student organization
had all decided ''to publicly support Draskovic, with the aim to
disrupt his vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   Indirectly, he was inferring that the U.S. and pro-Western
opposition had staged the shooting to drum up popular support for
Draskovic and discredit the Yugoslav government.
</P>
<P>
   The state Tanjug news agency also sought to dismiss Draskovic's
accusations and cast doubts on his account of the attack. ''It is
strange that Draskovic was shot at four times from the terrace of
his house, and that he suffered only a pierced ear and a light
flesh wound on his head,'' Tanjug said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Draskovic hurriedly left the scene, probably to think how to
concoct something,'' the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Tanjug said ''nobody in his right mind'' wanted to solve
political conflicts ''through violence and assassinations.'' It
went on to repeat allegations that Montenegro's government is
subservient to the United States, which wants ''by hook or by
crook'' to bring to power ''obedient puppet politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Draskovic is undoubtedly of that kind,'' Tanjug said.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassed by the attack, Montenegrin authorities demoted two
senior security officers. Montenegro's interior minister, Vukasin
Maras, said he would offer his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Although Draskovic lives in Serbia, he regularly spends the
summer along the Adriatic coast in Montenegro. He ordinarily
travels with his own security, but two weeks ago his four
bodyguards were arrested in Belgrade for illegal weapons
possession.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
