<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, June 17, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
34 Low Caste India Villagers Killed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PATNA, India (AP) -- Black-garbed gunmen stormed a village while its
residents slept early Saturday, executing 34 women, children and old men after
the latest caste-related battle in India's poorest and most lawless province.
The attackers, identified as members of an upper-caste militia backed by rich
landlords, fought a gunbattle with several armed villagers for 2&AMP;frac12; hours
until the residents ran out of ammunition, said M.V. Rao, police superintendent
of the Aurangabad area in Bihar state, where the massacre took place. Then the
attackers stormed several homes and ordered the women, children and elders to
stand in a line. They were shot and killed.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Criticizes Security Lapse
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. (AP) -- George W. Bush chastised the Clinton administration
today for its handling of nuclear secrets at the Los Alamos weapons laboratory,
saying that ''America's nuclear security should not be a matter of lost and
found.'' Bush, appearing with his brother, Florida Gov. Jeb Bush, at the state
convention of the Veterans of Foreign Wars, also blamed the administration for a
''slow slide to military weakness'' shown through poor military recruiting and
low morale within the armed forces. The Texas governor pledged to rebuild
military strength with lighter and more lethal weapons. At Los Alamos, two
computer hard drives containing nuclear secrets were found yesterday and federal
investigators believe they are the ones that were missing for more than a month.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Strong Earthquake Rocks Iceland
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   REYKJAVIK, Iceland (AP) -- A strong earthquake shook southern Iceland on
Saturday, causing structural damage to houses in a village near the epicenter
but no known injuries. The U.S. Geological Survey in Washington D.C. said the
quake measured magnitude 6.6, which would make it the strongest in Iceland since
a 7.0-magnitude quake on May 6, 1912. Iceeland's meteorological institute said
Saturday's quake had a magnitude of about 5.7, although it said it hadn't
completed calculations. Scientists on the small Scandinavian island said the
quake had originated 5.6 miles south of Arnes, a tiny community near the village
of Hella, south of the capital, Reykjavik.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Navy Detains 56 Vieques Protesters
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Navy officers detained 56 demonstrators today
after they invaded the U.S. Navy bombing range on Vieques island and demanded
that the Navy leave. Among those detained on the small Puerto Rican island were
20 doctors -- from surgeons to general practitioners -- who said in a statement:
''We are a group representing Puerto Rican doctors who are concerned about the
health and future of the people of Vieques.'' All the protesters were cited to
appear in federal court to be charged with trespassing, Navy spokesman Robert
Nelson said. They were subsequently released.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
N. Korea Proposes Talks on Families
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- In another sign that North Korea may be opening
up, the country's Red Cross Saturday said talks should begin this month to
reunite families separated by the Korean War. The telegram to the South Korean
Red Cross was a surprisingly quick move to begin implementing one of a series of
agreements struck by the leaders of the two Koreas during their historic
three-day summit. An estimated 1.2 million war refugees from the North are
living in South Korea today. More than half are over the age of 60; more than
200,000 are in their 70s. Most left behind relatives in the North.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton: Tighten Biological Weapons Ban
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today renewed his suggestion that a new
global inspection system be created to detect and deter cheating on
international agreements that outlaw biological weapons. The president's appeal
came on the 75th anniversary of the Geneva agreement that first banned chemical
and biological weapons from the battlefield. ''Today, one of the greatest
threats to American and global security is the danger that adversary nations or
terrorist groups will obtain or use chemical or biological weapons,'' the
president said in a statement.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tiger Woods Takes 6-Stroke Lead
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Tiger Woods made history at the U.S. Open today,
finishing the second round with a record six-shot lead over Thomas Bjorn and
Miguel Angel Jimenez. Kirk Triplett and Jose Maria Olazabal, the only other
players below par, were at 1-under 141. Woods and the rest of the remaining
field, cut to 63 players for the final two rounds, were scheduled to play the
third round later today.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gonzalez Leads Tigers To 8-6 Win
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Juan Gonzalez hit a two-run homer today in the bottom of the
ninth inning and the Detroit Tigers sent the Cleveland Indians to their sixth
straight loss, 8-6. Gonzalez, who has been mentioned in trade rumors, began the
day batting .266 with just 24 RBIs, a low total for one of baseball's top
sluggers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
