<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Kohl Aide Won't Testify  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- A key figure in the party-financing scandal
surrounding former German Chancellor Helmut Kohl is expected to
refuse to testify before a parliamentary investigating committee.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Uwe Luethje, a former financial officer for Kohl's
Christian Democratic Party, told the committee Luethje will invoke
his right to avoid self-incrimination, the Berliner Morgenpost
reported Saturday. Prosecutor are investigating Luethje for
possible charges in the party's slush fund scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Luethje is believed to have detailed knowledge about a web of
secret campaign accounts run under Kohl, who chaired the Christian
Democratic Party from 1973 to 1998. If Luethje refuses to testify,
he will join three other former aides who have stonewalled the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Parliament opened an inquiry in February to examine whether
decisions under Kohl's 1982-98 government were bought -- something
Kohl hotly denies.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl touched off the scandal last fall by admitting he accepted
about $1 million in secret campaign contributions during the 1990s.
He refused to name the donors. Anonymous party donations in Germany
are illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal grew to include secret foreign accounts, more
unexplained millions in party funds and allegations of money
laundering. It also sparked the downfall of party leader Wolfgang
Schaeuble, who took over from Kohl after his 1998 election defeat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
