<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan in Morocco To Talk With King  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RABAT, Morocco (AP) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan made an
impromptu stopover in Rabat on Saturday to talk with Moroccan King
Mohammed VI about the disputed Western Sahara territory and the
situation in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Annan, who was starting a Middle East tour, also went to the
western port city of Casablanca for a meeting with Saudi Arabian
Crown Prince Abdallah Ibn Abdelaziz.
</P>
<P>
   He then headed to Iran, the starting point of the Mideast trip
that is to take him to Lebanon and Jordan, among other places.
</P>
<P>
   Annan told reporters in a brief statement that his talks with
the Moroccan king had been ''fruitful.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. chief alluded to Lebanon's rejection of the U.N.
verification of Israel's May 24 withdrawal from its southern border
areas, but gave no details. He said he had spoken by telephone with
both Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and with Lebanese President
Emile Lahoud, but did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with the visiting Saudi crown prince, Annan said:
''We discussed the means to maintain security in Lebanon and in the
region.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan's visit here comes ahead of July 28-29 talks in London on
the disputed Western Sahara territory. The talks -- to be headed by
Annan's special envoy James Baker -- bring together all protagonists
in the quarter-century-old dispute:
</P>
<P>
   Morocco claims the territory as its own; the Polisario Front of
rebels demands independence for the vast territory; Algeria
traditionally has backed the Polisario; and Mauritania shares a
border with the Western Sahara -- a stretch of desert along the
Atlantic coast of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   A first meeting May 14 in London bore no fruit.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has tried for nearly a decade to organize a
referendum on the territory's status, but that effort has been
blocked by squabbling over who should be allowed to cast a ballot.
A U.N. mission has identified 86,000 natives with a right to vote
in a referendum. But nearly 130,000 people who were rejected have
appealed.
</P>
<P>
   A ''third way'' that would give the region large autonomy while
keeping it attached to Morocco -- which annexed the territory when
Spain gave it up in 1975 -- has emerged in talks without ever being
officially evoked by either side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
