<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, June 17, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Criticizes Security Lapse
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. (AP) -- George W. Bush, appearing with his brother, Florida
Gov. Jeb Bush at the state convention of the Veterans of Foreign Wars,
criticized the Clinton administration's handling of nuclear secrets at the Los
Alamos weapons laboratory. ''America's nuclear security should not be a matter
of lost and found,'' said Bush. Bush also pledged to rebuild military strength
with lighter and more lethal weapons. At Los Alamos, two computer hard drives
containing nuclear secrets were found yesterday and federal investigators
believe they are the ones that were missing for more than a month.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Marine Corps Leader Boards Osprey
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHINA LAKE NAVAL AIR WEAPONS STATION, Calif. (AP) -- Hoping to quell fears
about the safety of the military aircraft that crashed and killed 19 Marines,
Gen. James L. Jones boarded an MV-22 Osprey today for the aircraft's first
passenger flight since the crash. The Osprey, a hybrid aircraft that hovers like
a helicopter and flies like a plane, has been under heavy scrutiny since April
8, when one of the five then in operation crashed while trying to land at an
airfield near Tucson, Ariz. After the 30-minute flight, Jones called the Osprey
a ''wonderful aircraft'' that is ready to begin carrying passengers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
34 Low Caste India Villagers Killed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PATNA, India (AP) -- Black-garbed gunmen stormed a village while its
residents slept early Saturday, executing 34 women, children and old men after
the latest caste-related battle in India's poorest and most lawless province.
The attackers, identified as members of an upper-caste militia backed by rich
landlords, fought a gunbattle with several armed villagers for 2&AMP;frac12; hours
until the residents ran out of ammunition, said M.V. Rao, police superintendent
of the Aurangabad area in Bihar state, where the massacre took place. Then the
attackers stormed several homes and ordered the women, children and elders to
stand in a line. They were shot and killed.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Strong Earthquake Rocks Iceland
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   REYKJAVIK, Iceland (AP) -- A strong earthquake shook southern Iceland on
Saturday, causing structural damage to houses in a village near the epicenter
but no known injuries. The U.S. Geological Survey in Washington D.C. said the
quake measured magnitude 6.6, which would make it the strongest in Iceland since
a 7.0-magnitude quake on May 6, 1912. Scientists on the small Scandinavian
island said the quake had originated 5.6 miles south of Arnes, a tiny community
near the village of Hella, south of the capital, Reykjavik.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Navy Detains 56 Vieques Protesters
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Navy officers detained 56 demonstrators today
after they invaded the U.S. Navy bombing range on Vieques island and demanded
that the Navy leave. Among those detained on the small Puerto Rican island were
20 doctors -- from surgeons to general practitioners -- who said in a statement:
''We are a group representing Puerto Rican doctors who are concerned about the
health and future of the people of Vieques.'' All the protesters were cited to
appear in federal court to be charged with trespassing, Navy spokesman Robert
Nelson said. They were subsequently released.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Md. Lightning Strike Kills One
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) -- Lightning struck nine people who had gathered under a
tree for shelter from a storm today, and one person was killed, authorities
said. It was unclear whether the lightning struck the tree first or the victims,
said fire spokesman Leonard Clark. The victims, ranging in age from 20 to 56,
were players and spectators from a rugby match interrupted by the storm at
Annapolis Middle School, Clark said. Two of the victims were in serious
condition at the University of Maryland Shock Trauma Center in Baltimore.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Groups Protest Jim Carrey Movie
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A coalition of mental health advocacy groups sees nothing
funny about Jim Carrey's new movie, ''Me, Myself &AMP; Irene,'' and wants some
changes in its advertising. Carrey plays a Rhode Island police officer who has
two personalities, one of them violent. That appears to be a negative portrayal
of the mentally ill, says the head of the National Mental Health Association,
which represents about 350 organizations nationwide. Carrey's character is
incorrectly identified as having schizophrenia instead of multiple personality
disorder, said Michael Faenza, the coalition's president and CEO.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tiger Woods Takes 6-Stroke Lead
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Tiger Woods made history at the U.S. Open today,
finishing the second round with a record six-shot lead over Thomas Bjorn and
Miguel Angel Jimenez. Kirk Triplett and Jose Maria Olazabal, the only other
players below par, were at 1-under 141 after two rounds.
</P>
