<HEADLINE> California Vets Home Fined  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BARSTOW, Calif. (AP) -- A veterans home was cited and fined
$64,500 in connection with three patient deaths and faces possible
revocation of its license.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Health Services cited a wide range of
violations in issuing six citations Friday against the 400-bed
California Veterans Home for aging and disabled veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the California Department of Veterans Affairs
disputed the allegations, and plan to appeal, said Jerry Rucker,
the department's under secretary.
</P>
<P>
   The citations grew out of a survey of the home by state health
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, health department officials said the home did
not pay close enough attention to a patient who died in February. A
coroner and a treating physician at the home said the man died
after choking on broccoli. Officials of the veterans home said he
died of a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   In another case, an unidentified patient died in a diabetic coma
after suffering a skyrocketing blood-sugar level that had not been
called to a doctor's attention. A review of records revealed that a
third patient received a powerful anti-seizure medication twice
daily for 70 days without a physician's order.
</P>
<P>
   The $64,500 in fines is the maximum allowed by law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
