<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Union official dies in car crash  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BROOKLYN, N.Y. (AP) - A vice president in the state's
second-largest public employees union was killed early Saturday in
an alcohol-related car accident, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Jean DeBow, 51, was vice president of the Public Employees
Federation, representing 54,000 professional, scientific and
technical workers, most of whom work in state government.
</P>
<P>
   She was a passenger in a car which was apparently struck by a
drunken driver about 5 a.m. Police have charged 26-year-old Erasmo
Torres of Brooklyn with driving while intoxicated.
</P>
<P>
   Dollie Williams, a PEF executive board member, was also in the
car with DeBow and was hospitalized with injuries. No charges were
lodged against Williams.
</P>
<P>
   DeBow was also national vice president of the Coalition of Labor
Union Women and a member of the Coalition of Black Trade Unionists.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a tremendous loss for me and a tremendous loss for the
labor movement,'' PEF president Roger E. Benson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
