<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Royals Hire Allard Baird As New GM  </HEADLINE>
By DOUG TUCKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- The Royals' new owner hired a new
general manager, promoting Allard Baird on Saturday to replace Herk
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   David Glass, who bought the team in April, had indicated his
long-range plan was to promote Baird, a 12-year veteran of the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ''Recently, Herk came to me and recommended that we make Allard
the general manager,'' Glass said. ''He felt like Allard was ready
and certainly has the ability and the enthusiasm to take on the
general manager's role and do it very, very well. It's never good
to procrastinate.''
</P>
<P>
   Baird, 38, becomes one of baseball's youngest GMs and Robinson
becomes the team's chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had passion as a coach and a teacher and thought I would
probably end up in the minor leagues as a manager or roving
instructor,'' Baird said. ''But it evolved into this over time and
I'm excited about it. It's a tremendous opportunity and an honor.
I'm eager to get going.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, appointed general manager 10 years ago by the team's
late founder, Ewing Kauffman, was the longest-tenured GM in the
American League.
</P>
<P>
   Although the small-market Royals have not appeared in the
postseason since winning the 1985 World Series, they are showing
evidence of dramatic improvement with several talented young
position players, including outfielders Carlos Beltran and Jermaine
Dye and infielders Joe Randa and Mike Sweeney. Going into Saturday
night's game against Oakland, they were one game over .500, and
with renewed interest stirring among fans.
</P>
<P>
   'Allard was a big part of that,'' said Robinson, a 30-year
Royals employee. ''There was no reason to wait. This just positions
us to be a much stronger organization and move forward. Allard is
very ready to take the job.''
</P>
<P>
   A native of Rochester, N.H., Baird joined the Royals as hitting
coach for the Class-A Appleton of the Midwest League in 1988 and
two years later was made territorial scouting supervisor for
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   After winning the Ewing Kauffman Award for outstanding
contributions to the scouting department in 1996, he was made
special assistant to the general manager. In September 1998, he was
promoted to vice president and assistant general manager of
baseball operations.
</P>
<P>
   Glass, who purchased the team for $96 million, has promised to
increase the payroll, which was $23 million on opening day.
</P>
<P>
   ''Money is a big part of the game. But money doesn't play,''
Baird said. ''Players play. When that first pitch is thrown, it
still comes down to the ability to play. That will continue to be
our concentration.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-17-00 2022 </TRAILER>
