<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man found guilty of killing senior citizen over drug money dispute  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FREEHOLD, N.J. (AP) - A 33-year-old Long Branch man was
convicted of murdering his 72-year-old friend by beating him to
death with a hammer after the older man refused to give him money
to buy crack cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   In convicting Donyelle Locust, a Superior Court jury on Friday
rejected his claims that he was coerced into confessing to the
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Amison, a retired Marine sergeant and union official, was
found bludgeoned to death at his Asbury Park home after he refused
to give Locust some cash on Feb. 11, 1999, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Locust had borrowed about $100 from Amison
earlier in the day, but apparently wanted more. When Amison refused
the second request, Locust waited until the older man had gone to
sleep and used a hammer from the house to strike him repeatedly in
the head, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy revealed multiple blunt force trauma to the head,
including skull fractures, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Locust then stole several items of jewelry, traded them in for
drugs and apparently got his fix, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Locust was friends with the man and did odd jobs for
him.
</P>
<P>
   Locust faces a minimum of 30 years in prison without parole when
he is sentenced in August by Superior Court Judge Patricia Del
Bueno Cleary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-17-00 2054 </TRAILER>
