<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Girl Needing Transplant, Graduates  </HEADLINE>
By STEVEN Du BOIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   McMINNVILLE, Ore. (AP) -- For one night at least, Brandy Stroeder
wasn't the face of a health care system that let her down.
</P>
<P>
   Walking confidently across the stage to a loud ovation, the
18-year-old dying from cystic fibrosis hugged school officials,
grasped her high-school diploma and raised her arms in victory as
her classmates applauded and cameras flashed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It meant everything to me, I just didn't want to stumble,''
Stroeder said after the Friday night ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Stroeder, who suffers from a disease that causes her body to
produce excessive mucus that clogs her lungs, has sued the state
because it won't pay for a potentially lifesaving double
transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon Health Plan, which extends Medicaid coverage to roughly
350,000 low-income Oregonians, pays for single transplants but
considers a simultaneous lung-and-liver transplant too experimental
and, at $250,000, too costly.
</P>
<P>
   Without it, Brandy is expected to die within two years.
</P>
<P>
   The state this week agreed to pay for tests to determine if
Stroeder is a good candidate for the operation, but still maintains
it will not pay for the actual procedure.
</P>
<P>
   At the McMinnville High School football stadium, Stroeder, who
wants to be a chef, looked as healthy as her classmates, and
certainly yelled louder.
</P>
<P>
   ''Brandy acts likes there's nothing going on, so we respect
that,'' said Katie Maynard, 18, who has known Stroeder since middle
school. ''It's not like she shows off, saying 'oh, look, I have
this disease' that's not her at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
