<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Children expected for summer of recovery in the United States  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - An exhausted group of 160 children suffering
from the effects of the Chernobyl radiation leak came to the United
States Saturday to live with American families and rejuvenate their
bodies with abundant food and medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The 8- and 9-year-olds were met Saturday night at John F.
Kennedy International Airport in Queens by 20 volunteer pilots for
AirLifeLine, a group of more than 1,100 pilots nationwide who
donate their time, fuel and planes to fly financially needy
patients to distant medical facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots such as 34-year-old Alex Wattles of Pound Ridge, N.Y.,
arrived to take the Chernobyl children to St. Louis, Philadelphia,
Mannassas, Va. and Youngstown, Ohio, where families will take them
in. Other children remained in New York City. They will return to
Chernobyl in the Ukraine on Aug. 11.
</P>
<P>
   ''They don't look so good when you pick them up for the first
time in June. They're gray and pale and skinny. They look worn
down,'' Wattles said. ''Come August, they look great. Their cheeks
are flushed. They're filled out and well rested.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chernobyl atomic power plant's reactor No. 4 exploded and
caught fire on April 26, 1986, spreading a highly radioactive cloud
over much of Europe in the most serious nuclear accident in
history.
</P>
<P>
   This is the seventh year that Chernobyl children have been taken
in by families with children of their own. Each year, the number
brought in grows. This year, 30 more children arrived than last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Alison Reiner, a spokeswoman for the group, said the children
generally arrive in poor health, though none of them are terminally
ill.
</P>
<P>
   She said they visit eye doctors, dentists, pediatricians and
specialists while eating more nutritious foods and breathing
fresher air.
</P>
<P>
   Wattles said the children throughout the summer will be ''doing
all the things you and I take for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Their activities sometimes include visits to amusement parks,
baseball games and cultural events.
</P>
<P>
   Wattles recalled how one boy upon his first visit to a
convenience store said: ''I've never seen so much food in my life.
Is this where they keep all the food in the United States?''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was taking eight children to St. Louis and would
return to New York City with them at the end of the summer, in what
he predicted would be a tearful goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very emotional thing,'' he said. ''They're very
gracious and grateful to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   AirLifeLine: http:// www.airlifeline.org
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (877) AIR-LIFE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-17-00 2114 </TRAILER>
