<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton rips Lazio for missing oil vote  </HEADLINE>
By RIK STEVENS
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALTAMONT, N.Y. (AP) - Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton on
Saturday accused her Republican opponent of failing to stand up for
New Yorkers by missing a vote aimed at easing high oil costs.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio was an early champion of the measure to
spend $10 million to establish a 2-million barrel home heating oil
reserve. But when the House of Representatives voted at 9 p.m.
Thursday, Lazio was already headed for New York to get back on the
campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was defeated 195-193 and some supporters said Lazio's
presence could have made the difference.
</P>
<P>
   At a campaign stop in front of about 5,000 Albany County
Democrats, Clinton said Lazio's decision to campaign rather that
vote should raise questions about his commitment to New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was very disappointed because he missed the vote on the
northeast oil reserve, something I had called for months ago as a
way of answering some of the challenges we face here in the
northeast when it comes to affordable home heating oil and gasoline
prices,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he had been there, it might have made all the difference,''
Clinton said. ''I think it's really a shame that when we needed a
vote for the Northeast strategic oil reserve, he was missing in
action. Because, you know, that's the kind of vote that could
literally save New Yorkers millions and millions of dollars and
make a difference on what people could afford on limited or fixed
incomes.''
</P>
<P>
   Since his nomination in May as the Republican candidate for the
Senate seat being vacated by Daniel P. Moynihan, Lazio has said he
will continue his work in Congress while campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   Sources on Capitol Hill told Newsday they were surprised he left
before the vote, having cosponsored the original proposal to create
a $10-million oil reserve to be stored in tanks in New York Harbor
and released in times of shortages.
</P>
<P>
   Dan McLagan, a Lazio spokesman, told Newsday the congressman
hopes to revive the funding in a House-Senate conference committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio campaign did not immediately return calls Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also defended her latest round of ads that attack
Lazio's vote against the Patients' Bill of Rights and his
opposition to a bill to increase penalties when a crime is bias
related. Clinton said the ads are not so much a negative tactic as
they are about issues important to the voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think this is campaign based on differences on issues and
there are very clear differences and contrasts between me and my
opponent and I'm going to be pointing them out,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has said he voted against the health care bill because he
believes it will benefit lawyers rather than patients. He says he
supports the hate crimes law that passed in the state Senate, but
abstained in 1990 while serving in the Suffolk County Legislature
on a measure calling for a hate crimes law to be enacted in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   He has characterized the ads as ''desperate.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton declined to criticize a reported stock deal in which
Lazio turned a $2,300 investment into about $16,000 by buying
options in a brokerage company right before it was taken over by
Fleet Financial Group. Two former executives at the brokerage firm
said they and other company officials donated at least $35,000 to
Lazio campaigns since 1995 but said there was no discussion of the
company stock and Lazio said he had no inside information about the
pending Fleet takeover when he bought the options.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't know all the facts yet,'' Clinton said. ''The stories
that have been written raise some serious questions that I think
he'll have to answer and then it will be up to New Yorkers to
decide.''
</P>
<P>
   In attendance at Saturday's picnic was Andrew Cuomo, U.S.
Secretary of Housing and Urban Development and son of former
governor Mario M. Cuomo. The younger Cuomo has been mentioned as a
possible Democratic gubernatorial candidate in 2002 and sounded
like one Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Republican leadership in the state hasn't done what they
needed to do to bring the economy back,'' Cuomo said. ''It's not
going to be that way for long.''
</P>
<P>
   In Buffalo later Saturday, Clinton addressed about 300 people at
an Erie County Democratic Committee dinner where she thanked
Buffalo Mayor Anthony Masiello for calling her a ''Buffalonian.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I will wear it proudly,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   During her 20-minute remarks, which were moved up to beat the
start of a reggae concert at the Buffalo Convention Center, she
stressed her commitment to education, health care reform and social
security, keeping her attacks on Lazio relatively low-key.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most of those serving on the other side have always voted the
way they were told, not necessarily the way that was in the best
interest of the people they represented,'' she said. ''I will not
be making decisions based on what anyone tells me I need to do to
get ahead. I don't need to get ahead, I just need to do what's
right for the people of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Attending the Buffalo black-tie event were H. Carl McCall,
another potential gubernatorial candidate in 2002, and U.S. Rep.
John LaFalce.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
