<HEADLINE> Indians' Ramirez Homers in Minors  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   AKRON, Ohio (AP) -- Cleveland Indians outfielder Manny Ramirez,
playing in his first minor league game since 1993, hit a two-run
home run Saturday in his rehab assignment for a strained left
hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez, out since May 29, with a strained left hamstring, was
in the Akron lineup as a designated hitter against Altoona in a
Double-A Eastern League game.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, Ramirez hit a pitch from Steve Sparks over
the left-field fence in the third inning. He struck out looking in
the first inning and walked in the fifth and seventh.
</P>
<P>
   With the score 3-3, Ramirez drew a walk to lead off the seventh,
but he was thrown out at second on Jon Hamilton's attempted
sacrifice bunt. Ramirez's running on the play appeared to be
hampered.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez was batting .322 with 13 homers and 47 RBIs for the
Indians when he was injured while running out a grounder against
Anaheim on May 29. Last season, Ramirez drove in 165 runs, the
highest RBI total in baseball in more than 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Aeros were the Canton-Akron Indians in 1993, when Ramirez
hit .340 with 17 homers in 89 Eastern League games.
</P>
<P>
   Akron beat Altoona 4-3 in the first game of a doubleheader.
Ramirez sat out the second game.
</P>
</TEXT>
