<DOCNO> APW20000617.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Marion Jones Loses Long Jump  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID DROSCHAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Fans bearing cameras, placards and words of
encouragement came to see track star Marion Jones on Saturday. But
her training mate -- and husband -- stole the show at the Pontiac
Grand Prix Invitational meet.
</P>
<P>
   Chandra Sturrup of the Bahamas won the 100 meters in the meet's
first event at 11.09 seconds, then rushed over to the long jump pit
and beat workout partner Jones with a leap of 21 feet, 11&AMP;frac34; inches.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anytime I compete I love to win, I thrive on winning and when
I don't I'm a little sour,'' said Jones, who didn't run in the 100,
one of her strongest events. ''But this is going to motivate me to
keep on keeping at it.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Jones was fouling on her last of six long jump
attempts, husband C.J. Hunter was wrapping up the shot put victory
with a world-best throw of 71-8&AMP;frac34;. The 1999 winner at the World
Championships also had the previous best this season of 71-4 in
April.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know he is the best in the world,'' Jones said. ''You
(reporters) are the ones who seem surprised, not us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Prix meet was the first of three such events in the
Golden Spike Tour leading up to the U.S. Olympic trials July 14-23
at Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, trying to qualify in five events for the Sydney Olympics,
had a pair of best jumps at 21-6 Saturday, much better than her
leap of 20-7 in Japan in May. However, Jones admitted she has more
work before the trials.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is experimenting on more speed on the runway and less
power on her leap. There was progress, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have had problems in the long jump and heard my share of
criticism, but I still feel very confident,'' Jones said. ''I'm
still the same person who jumped in 1998, nothing has changed. I
just have to get a little more confident in my jumping and things
will fall in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones' best long jump was 23-11&AMP;frac34; two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''I went for it on the last jump,'' Jones said. ''I know I
fouled, but I had a feeling it was pretty far. It is going to
happen. I am going to leave it all out on the track. I'm not going
to take any home.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter also got pushed by Adam Nelson, who threw a personal best
70-2&AMP;frac12; in an event that also included 1996 Olympic silver medalist
John Godina and 2000 indoor champion Andy Bloom. Hunter and Nelson
traded the lead several times before Hunter got his winning throw
on his fifth attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ''He sent some people home thinking about what they thought was
going to be an easy spot on the (Olympic) team,'' Hunter said of
Nelson. ''He certainly confused the issue a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Sturrup, who will try to qualify for four events for the Bahamas
next month, was thrilled this event was held on her home training
grounds -- a track she shares with Jones and other top track stars.
A late addition to the event, she is long jumping for the first
time since she was at Norfolk State in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was to my advantage that I train on this track every day,''
Sturrup said of the Paul Derr Track at North Carolina State. ''It
really helped in the long jump, knowing where my mark was and
trying to see if I can do the same things I do in practice every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it was a good day for some of the older U.S. runners.
Mike Marsh and Antonio Pettigrew -- each 32 -- won the 100 and 400
races respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Marsh, who ran a wind-aided 9.90 April 16 at the Mt. SAC Relays,
was competing against top-level competition for first time in 18
months after having bone spurs removed from his left foot. The gold
winner in the 200 at the 1992 Olympics, ran a 10.01, edging
Auburn's Coby Miller at 10.04.
</P>
<P>
   Marsh's impressive time came after two false starts by an
anxious field.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are a lot of differences I notice physically. I don't
have the same body that I had at 26,'' Marsh said of a group of
young sprinters he'll challenge at the trials. ''It takes me a
little longer to recover. I am like an old car -- I really have to
take care of it.
</P>
<P>
   ''But at the same time, I celebrate my age. Just like the false
starts, I've seen things, I've been through things that a lot of
those guys have yet to see. There is very little now that surprises
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettigrew, who also trains here, ran 44.65 after slowing up over
the final 100 meters because of a cramp in his right thigh.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have 5&AMP;frac12; weeks before the Olympic trials, so you have to
start picking it up,'' Pettigrew said. ''Everybody will start
running a little faster now because we start jockeying for
position.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
