<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, June 17, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Criticizes Security Lapse
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. (AP) -- At a state convention of the Veterans of foreign
wars, George W. Bush criticized the Clinton administration's handling of nuclear
secrets at the Los Alamos weapons laboratory. ''America's nuclear security
should not be a matter of lost and found,'' said Bush. Bush, appearing with his
brother, Florida Gov. Jeb Bush, also pledged to rebuild military strength with
lighter and more lethal weapons. At Los Alamos, two computer hard drives
containing nuclear secrets were found yesterday and federal investigators
believe they are the ones that were missing for more than a month.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Death Penalty Recommended For Ala. Trucker
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COLUMBIANA, Ala. (AP) -- A jury today recommended the death penalty for a
truck driver convicted of capital murder in a rampage that left three men dead.
Alan Eugene Miller, 35, walked into two businesses, complained his co-workers
there were spreading rumors about him, and then shot them. Shelby County Circuit
Judge Al Crowson said he would schedule final sentencing later. He can either
accept or reject jurors' suggestion. Miller was charged with gunning down Lee
Holdbrooks and Scott Yancy at Ferguson Enterprises, the company where he worked.
Then, prosecutors said, he drove to Post Airgas, a company that had fired him,
and shot Terry Jarvis.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Colorado Firefighters Making Progress
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BAILEY, Colo. (AP) -- Firefighters worked in rain and light snow today to cut
off two wildfires burning in the foothills of the Rocky Mountains. Some
homeowners were left with nothing; others found houses mercifully spared by the
blazes that have blackened nearly 21,000 acres and destroyed 54 homes since
Monday. Robert McCoy, who lives in a nearby subdivision, said 11 homes were
destroyed on his street. He described the neighborhood he drove through to reach
as his home as a black forest that was total destruction.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
N. Ireland Police, Protesters Clash
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LURGAN, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Protesters hurled firebombs at security
officers monitoring a Protestant parade in this town Saturday, and police fired
back with plastic bullets. Three police officers and a soldier were slightly
injured and one man was arrested after about an hour of fighting, a Royal Ulster
Constabulary spokesman said. The Orange Order, Northern Ireland's largest
Protestant fraternal group, had received permission from the Parades Commission
to march through Lurgan town center, about 20 miles southwest of Belfast.
Hundreds of troops and police in riot gear had sealed flashpoint areas in
Lurgan, but they came under attack by dozens of anti-parade protesters who threw
fire bombs, ball bearings, bottles and stones.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
34 Low Caste India Villagers Killed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PATNA, India (AP) -- Black-garbed gunmen stormed a village while its
residents slept early Saturday, executing 34 women, children and old men after
the latest caste-related battle in India's poorest and most lawless province.
The attackers, identified as members of an upper-caste militia backed by rich
landlords, fought a gunbattle with several armed villagers for 2&AMP;frac12; hours
until the residents ran out of ammunition, said M.V. Rao, police superintendent
of the Aurangabad area in Bihar state, where the massacre took place. Then the
attackers stormed several homes and ordered the women, children and elders to
stand in a line. They were shot and killed.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Seven Die in Texas Car Accident
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VAN HORN, Texas (AP) -- A car clipped a vehicle being towed by a
tractor-trailer truck on an interstate in west Texas today, killing seven
people. The Texas Department of Public Safety said a 1998 Pontiac was trying to
pass a truck that was towing a 1994 Nissan in which four California residents
were riding. Both were eastbound on Interstate-10, DPS spokesman Mike Cox said.
Cox said the Pontiac cut too close, and the truck steered onto the shoulder of
the highway. The Pontiac collided with the towed Nissan, which broke loose and
both vehicles went spinning through the air. Everyone in both vehicles died in
the accident, Cox said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tiger Woods Leads U.S. Open
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Tiger Woods made history at the U.S. Open today
with a six-stroke lead after 36 holes at Pebble Beach. Miguel Angel Jimenez of
Spain and Thomas Bjorn of Denmark, who started the third round six strokes off
the pace, quickly dropped out of sight.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Blue Jays Defeat Red Sox 11-10
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Toronto nearly blew a 10-run lead as David Wells tied Randy
Johnson for the major league lead with his 11th win and the Blue Jays hung on
for an 11-10 win over the Boston Red Sox today. Tony Batista avenged a rough
game one night earlier by homering in his first at-bat and Alex Gonzalez drove
in four runs with a two-run homer and two-run single. Brad Fullmer had a two-run
homer and Jose Cruz added a two-run double as Toronto built an 11-1 lead in the
fifth inning.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
