<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Illinois man has miles to mow before he sleeps  </HEADLINE>
By JEFF LINKOUS
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The way Gary Hatter sees it, he has a
little more than 3,100 miles to go before he makes the cut.
</P>
<P>
   Hatter, 46, is driving a bright orange lawn tractor in a quest
to land himself in the Guinness Book of World Records for the
longest distance traveled on a riding mower. The record is 4,039
miles over 51 days.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday morning, the Champaign, Ill., man rolled down
Barrack Street in Trenton with his 17-year-old son, Gary Jr.,
following in a car. When he pulled up to the New Jersey Statehouse
on his 17th day of driving, an odometer he added to his Kubota
mower read 877.9.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yee-hah!'' he said as he coasted to a stop in a parking lot a
just off the Statehouse. Showing off his mower, Hatter held up a
block of wood he uses to trap the mower's accelerator in a down
position. ''This is my cruise control,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one years ago, Hatter had a higher highway vantage point
and more horses under the hood. He drove trucks for a food company
but injured his back unloading milk. Two operations have failed to
remedy the spinal disk degeneration he suffers, and he has been
unable to work since.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Guinness Book of Records is kind of secondary,'' said
Hatter, adding that his primary goal is to raise money for a third
operation.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has raised $425 through donations and selling
checkered flags for $5 that he autographs.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hopes a third operation will stave off nerve damage
that doctors have told him could leave him paralyzed. He said he
long ago exhausted his medical insurance. He estimates he needs
$100,000 to cover the operation and related physical therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Hatter began his trek June 1 in Maine, where he bought the
22-horsepower lawn tractor with money lent to him. Along the way -
through New Hampshire, Massachusetts and Connecticut - he has
gotten cheers from onlookers and encouragement from police who have
stopped him to find out why there was a man chugging down the
highway on a mower at 9 mph.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Hatter rolled into New York City. He drew plenty
of attention and even some perks: complimentary front-row seats to
Thursday's taping of ''Late Night With David Letterman.'' When he
left the city, he said, New York's finest escorted him through the
Lincoln Tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wasn't sure how I was going to get out of New York City,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   From Trenton, Hatter planned to head to Philadelphia, then
Wilmington, Del. From there, it's Baltimore and Washington, then
more points south.
</P>
<P>
   Before heading out of Trenton, Hatter, with a bridge crossing
into Pennsylvania to his back, paused to asked a reporter for
directions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-17-00 2208 </TRAILER>
