<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Last Look for Nicklaus After US Open  </HEADLINE>
By JIM LITKE
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- The slogan du jour on the PGA Tour
is, ''These guys are good.'' The reality, though, is that one guy
is just too good for all the others.
</P>
<P>
   The only golfer Tiger Woods fears anymore is himself. The old
strategy of waiting for him to screw up is a waste of time now.
He's been in real trouble exactly twice through three rounds of the
U.S. Open and managed to extricate himself quite nicely both times,
thank you.
</P>
<P>
   One came at No. 3 on Saturday, when he dumped his approach shot
into gnarly rough behind a greenside bunker, tried unsuccessfully
to hack out sideways, and wound up making a triple-bogey. But a
slew of birdies quickly cleaned up that mess.
</P>
<P>
   Another bad shot caused the other hiccup, but cleaning up proved
a little stickier. Earlier in the morning, Woods had to play six
holes to complete a second round postponed by darkness Friday. At
the 18th, he hooked his drive into the ocean and talked to himself
in terms only a sailor would repeat.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of us were treated to the outburst because NBC had a
boom microphone near the tee box. The ball had barely settled in
the rocks lining Carmel Bay when announcer Johnny Miller deftly
applied some damage control: ''Not much more to be said about that
shot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Woods went on to make a remarkable bogey, and proof that his
maturity now extends beyond the course came a short while later. He
is still just 24 and not far removed from the days when emotion was
like jet fuel for his play. But informed by friends that his
cursing made it to live TV, Woods gracefully apologized.
</P>
<P>
   A clear conscience is nice, but the most varied and powerful
game ever seen is probably more important to someone determined to
become the greatest golfer ever. All of that was on display in
Saturday's up-and-down round, which Woods closed out at even-par
71. That left him at 8 under, the only player in red, 10 shots
clear of the pack pursuing him into the final round.
</P>
<P>
   ''I played solid golf,'' Woods said. ''I thought if I hit a lot
of fairways and greens, I'd pick up a couple of strokes.''
</P>
<P>
   When he hoists the trophy over his head Sunday evening, the
numbers might be even more eye-popping than they are now. Woods
already has claimed the record for biggest lead after both the
second and third rounds and his 36-hole total of 134 tied Jack
Nicklaus and two others for the lowest ever. But glance at his play
over the last 20 tour events, where Woods has 11 victories, and his
dominance looks clearer still.
</P>
<P>
   Like Nicklaus, his model, he's learned spectacular golf can stir
the soul, but solid golf wins more often and it's easier on the
nerves.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing out the Sprint International last August -- a tournament
that uses the quirky Stableford scoring system -- Woods has finished
in the top 20 at every tournament he's played in since Bay Hill in
early 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Revealingly, he's needed just two rounds in the 60s to seal
those 11 wins. His run of top-20 finishes in the majors stretches
back even further, to the 1997 PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   What Woods has done is cut out nearly all the spectacular
failures -- double and triple bogeys -- and let opponents take the
high-risk road to catch him. So far the results have been
impossible to argue with.
</P>
<P>
   He will walk away from Pebble Beach and toward next month's
British Open at St. Andrews a more prohibitive favorite than ever,
capable of completing the career Grand Slam two years earlier than
Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus was always Woods' benchmark and much has been made of
the fact that the Golden Bear made his exit at the place where
Woods began building his Open legacy in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   The search for the next Nicklaus took longer than expected and
more people auditioned for the role than should have been allowed.
But as Woods slips on one more jacket that Nicklaus wore, there is
no longer any questions about the fit.
</P>
<P>
   When Woods tore through the field at the Memorial two weeks ago
-- tearing up Nicklaus' finest work as a course designer in the
bargain -- worries about the lack of a dominant player were replaced
by those of a player who had become too dominant.
</P>
<P>
   ''People mention Brad Faxon or Jim Furyk when they talk about
the best putter on tour,'' Paul Goydos said, ''and Tiger is as good
or better than they are. Guys mention Justin Leonard as the best
chipper. Tiger is a better chipper. People talk about David Duval
and Greg Norman driving the ball long and straight. Tiger is longer
and straighter.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is overwhelming the game right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The scenery changes, the reality does not.
</P>
<P>
   The guy is too good.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Jim Litke is the national sports columnist for The Associated
Press. Write to him at jlitke@ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
