<HEADLINE> Alleged ringleader: ''I'm not involved'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - The alleged ringleader of the Central Park gang
that sexually assaulted dozens of women last weekend insisted that
he was ''doing nothing'' when the attacks began.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sitting there having fun, you know?'' said Manuel Vargas,
18, as he was led from the 13th Precinct in handcuffs on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas is one of 16 suspects arrested so far in connection with
the incident following the Puerto Rican Day Parade. Three of the
suspects arrested are from New Jersey. Police said Saturday that
they were seeking additional suspects identified from amateur
videotapes that captured the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The NYPD has assigned more than 75 detectives full-time to
identifying and arresting the suspects. Police Internal Affairs
investigators are also checking into reports that some officers
failed to help the victims of the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas, of the Bronx, claimed he had nothing to do with the
incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're telling me that I was involved,'' the high school
dropout said. ''I was just sitting there doing nothing. I'm not
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Police report that 50 women - including two British tourists a
French newlywed and two New Jersey women - have reported that they
were attacked by the rampaging gang. Victims were doused with water
before the men began tearing away their clothes and pawing at them.
</P>
<P>
   At a Friday night arraignment for some of the suspects,
Assistant District Attorney Leemie Kahng painted a chilling picture
of the defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects belonged to ''a malicious mob that literally took
over the southern and western parts of Central Park ... and
horrified not only the city, but the world,'' Kahng said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a fourth woman announced plans for a $7 million
lawsuit against the Police Department, charging that officers
failed to come to her aid when the groping began.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were animals,'' said a teary 25-year Jasmine Gonzalez of
Brooklyn. ''There were no men in the park.''
</P>
</TEXT>
