<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Open Notebook  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL NEWBERRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Nick Price was feeling better after
making the cut in the U.S. Open. As for his homeland, that's quite
a different matter.
</P>
<P>
   Price grew up in Zimbabwe, now embroiled in racial turmoil. At
least 31 people, most of them opponents of President Robert Mugabe,
have been killed in political violence since February, and many
more have been beaten.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe has expressed sympathy with the mobs of black supporters
illegally occupying more than 1,400 white-owned farms. Zimbabwe was
formerly named Rhodesia and ruled by the white minority until 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's awful there,'' said Price, who is white. ''My biggest
priority is my health and my family's health, but outside of that,
it's what is going on in my country. It's a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Price manages to put those issues aside when he's on the course,
as he showed by finishing the second round at Pebble Beach with a
1-under 70 Saturday morning -- good enough to make the cut after an
opening 77. He slumped in the afternoon, putting up a 78 in the
stiff winds.
</P>
<P>
   His homeland is never far from his thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ''I get 20 e-mails a day telling me what's going on down
there,'' said Price, who now lives in Hobe Sound, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Vijay Singh, a native of Fiji, doesn't want to get involved in
his country's problems, which began May 19. A rebel leader is
holding the deposed prime minister and 30 other hostages at
gunpoint in parliament to press demands that Fiji's ethnic Indian
minority be stripped of political power.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a sad thing,'' said Singh, who lives in Ponte Vedra
Beach, Fla. ''I hope they get it sorted out. But whatever I say,
it's not going to make a difference back home. I'll leave it to
them to settle that.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   MONTY'S WOES: Playing with Ernie Els seems to bring out the
worst in Colin Montgomerie.
</P>
<P>
   The British star struggled to a 79 in Saturday's third round,
falling apart with a quadruple bogey at No. 8. That was the low
point in a stretch of six holes he played at 9-over -- on the first
six and last six, he had one birdie and 11 pars.
</P>
<P>
   ''My irons are terrible and that's what I've been suffering
with,'' Montgomerie said. ''I just played badly, pure and simply.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie required two swings out of the rough around the
eighth green to move the ball the length of his wedge. He finally
chipped out and settled for an 8 on the way to his worst score in
36 U.S. Open rounds.
</P>
<P>
   His previous high was a 78, which came in a 1994 playoff that
also included Loren Roberts and was won by Ernie Els.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie was pared again Saturday with Els, who shot a
brilliant 3-under 68 to get back on the leaderboard.
</P>
<P>
   ''He always seems to play well with me in the U.S. Open,'' Monty
said dryly.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   HAPPY 80: Jeff Coston, a golf instructor playing in the U.S.
Open for the first time in 22 years, wasn't the least bit concerned
about shooting an 80 in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he thoroughly enjoyed himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is so much better than the first time,'' the 44-year-old
Coston said, referring to his 79-79 showing in the 1977 Open. ''I
missed the cut and left the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   In '78, Coston went home early again after rounds of 89-84.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was playing with a club pro from Texas,'' remembered Coston,
who now teaches at a golf academy in Blaine, Wash. ''He said,
'Where do you work, because you obviously don't play golf for a
living.'''
</P>
<P>
   After finally qualifying for the Open again this year, Coston
opened with a 1-under 70 and made the cut by two strokes with a 77
in the second round. He was being assisted in the stiff winds by
his 19-year-old son, Tyler, who doubled as his caddie.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel I played way better today than I did yesterday,''
Coston said after his 9-over showing Saturday. ''Yesterday, I felt
like I was leaking oil and needed a new carburetor.''
</P>
<P>
   Displaying the wit that made him a favorite in the interview
area, Coston was asked to describe Pebble Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ''The golf course is always changing character: sunny, foggy,
windy,'' he said. ''They're related, but it's not the same
person.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   TRASHY SHOT: Angel Cabrera had golf's version of the
3-pointer, sending his drive at the par-3 12th into a trash can on
the right side of the green.
</P>
<P>
   Cabrera was completing a weather-delayed second round when he
sliced his tee shot, which bounced once and plopped right in the
container. He was allowed to take a drop without penalty and,
thankfully, clean his ball. He wound up with a bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes you make a mistake,'' Cabrera, a native of
Argentina, said through a translator. ''This time, it just happened
to go in the garbage bin.''
</P>
<P>
   The shot epitomized a trashy morning all around for Cabrera, who
was 2-under when he started play. He shot a 5-over 41 on the back
nine to drop from contention heading into the third round.
</P>
<P>
   Told that his shot might be called a two-pointer in the United
States, Cabrera smiled and said, ''Three points!''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   TIN CUP II: Rick Hartman, a club pro from New York, fulfilled
at least part of the script written by his caddie, who also doubles
as an actor, director and screenwriter.
</P>
<P>
   Don Michael Paul of Los Angeles met Hartman at the Pebble Beach
Invitational last year. They remained friends and when Hartman
qualified for the U.S. Open, he asked Paul to serve as his caddie.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wrote a little script and sent it to him,'' Paul said. ''In
my script, he wins it. He hits a wedge from the rocks for an eagle
at 18.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartman, 41, is unlikely to win his first Open, but he made the
cut Saturday with a 6-over 148. His caddie was more excited than he
was, jumping around so much that Hartman had to tell him to calm
down a few times.
</P>
<P>
   As for Hartman, he planned to enjoy the final two rounds, having
accomplished his main goal.
</P>
<P>
   ''Playing on the weekend in the U.S. Open at Pebble Beach,'' he
said, glancing toward the Pacific Ocean as he stood at 18. ''Not
too bad.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   MAYFAIR ON THE MOUND: Phoenix native Billy Mayfair had
something to look forward to after rounds of 83-76 in the U.S.
Open. He'll be throwing out the first pitch in the Arizona
Diamondbacks game on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was supposed to do it last year in Game 5, but they got beat
in New York,'' he said, alluding to the NL playoff series won by
the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   How's the arm? Mayfair isn't sure but said, ''I'm not the Big
Unit.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   DQ'D: Kyle Blackman was disqualified when he signed his
scorecard with the wrong score at the 18th hole Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was a mere technicality. Blackman finished with
back-to-back 78s and didn't make the cut anyway. He still receives
$1,000, as does every players who fails to make it past the first
two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EUROPEAN SUCCESS: Tony Jacklin is the only European to win the
U.S. Open since the 1920s. That streak won't end this year, thanks
to Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   But the leaderboard after the third round showed those from
across the Atlantic are getting the hang of America's toughest
test.
</P>
<P>
   The top 11 included five Europeans: Miguel Angel Jimenez and
Jose Maria Olazabal of Spain, Lee Westwood and Nick Faldo of
England, and Padraig Harrington of Ireland. Two other foreign-born
players -- South Africa's Ernie Els and New Zealand's Michael
Campbell -- left only four Americans in the other spots.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's great to see all your partners up there,'' Jimenez said.
''It shows you there are great players all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   And that list doesn't even include Denmark's Thomas Bjorn, who
played in the final pairing with Woods but collapsed to 22nd place
with an 82 Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''You hear on TV all the time over here that we can't play in
the Open,'' Bjorn said. ''But look at that leaderboard. I don't see
too many Americans up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods has a 10-shot lead over Els, while Harrington and Jimenez
were 11 shots back.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our top 12 is not far behind their top 12,'' Bjorn said.
''Tiger is way ahead of everybody else. But the rest of the top 12
is very close.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a new generation of European golfers is getting adjusted
to U.S. Open-style courses -- narrow fairways, thick rough and tiny,
fast greens. Maybe one of them will someday follow in the footsteps
of Jacklin, an Englishman who won the 1970 Open.
</P>
<P>
   ''All the guys have been here a couple of times now,'' Bjorn
said. ''We're getting used to what it takes to win over here.''
</P>
<P>
   Not this year, though.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
