<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-17 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, June 17, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Two Colo. Fires 70 Pct. Contained
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BAILEY, Colo. (AP) -- As residents shoveled ashes from their yards and sifted
through the rubble of their charred homes Saturday, firefighters worked in rain
and light snow to cut off two wildfires burning in the foothills of the Rocky
Mountains. Both fires were about 70 percent contained by midday Saturday,
allowing officials to send some firefighters to work on blazes in California,
Arizona and New Mexico. Meanwhile, government leaders began assessing damage to
the environment, including water resources metropolitan Denver relies on.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gunmen Execute 34 in Indian Village
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PATNA, India (AP) -- Black-garbed gunmen stormed a village while its
residents slept early Saturday, executing 34 women, children and old men after
the latest caste-related battle in India's poorest and most lawless province.
The attackers, identified as members of an upper-caste militia backed by rich
landlords, fought a gunbattle with several armed villagers for 2&AMP;frac12; hours
until the residents ran out of ammunition, said M.V. Rao, police superintendent
of the Aurangabad area in Bihar state, where the massacre took place. Then the
attackers stormed several homes and ordered the women, children and elders to
stand in a line. They were shot and killed.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Girl Needing Double Transplant Graduates
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   McMINNVILLE, Ore. (AP) -- Brandy Stroeder, an 18-year-old in need of a a
double transplant, acheived her lifetime goal, graduating from high school. ''It
meant everything to me, I just didn't want to stumble,'' Stroeder said after the
Friday night ceremony. Stroeder, who suffers from a disease that causes her body
to produce excessive mucus that clogs her lungs, has sued the state because it
won't pay for a potentially lifesaving double transplant. Oregon Health Plan,
which extends Medicaid coverage to roughly 350,000 low-income Oregonians, pays
for single transplants but considers a simultaneous lung-and-liver transplant
too experimental and, at $250,000, too costly. Without it, Brandy is expected to
die within two years.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian's Kin Send Castro a Greeting
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Elian Gonzalez and the rest of his family sent a Father's Day
greeting to President Fidel Castro on the eve of a huge Saturday rally in Cuba
to protest the 6-year-old's extended stay in the United States. ''On this
Father's Day we want to send you an affectionate greeting and a deserved kiss
from all of us,'' read the letter sent to Castro and all Cuban fathers and read
Friday night on state television. Hours after the letter was read, more than
300,000 people gathered for the largest rally held in the Cuban countryside
since early December.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gunfire Erupts in S. Leone Capital
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Residents dashed for cover Saturday as gunfire
rang out in the streets of Freetown, Sierra Leone's capital. The source of the
half-hour burst of small-arms fire was not immediately clear. The shooting was
heaviest around the main prison, where members of the rebel Revolutionary United
Front have been jailed since they reignited the country's eight-year civil war.
U.N. peacekeepers and government soldiers were patrolling the city, U.N.
spokesman David Wimhurst said. Sporadic gunfire continued for about two hours
after the main outburst as armed soldiers raced through the city in military and
civilian vehicles. At about 11 p.m., however, the city fell silent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mrs. Clinton Visits Mrs. Roosevelt's Home
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HYDE PARK, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton made a pilgrimage Saturday to
the home of her hero, Eleanor Roosevelt, a former first lady who declined a
challenge the current one has taken on -- a run for the U.S. Senate. Clinton
came to Val-Kill, Eleanor Roosevelt's cottage home and a national historic site,
to announce that $150,000 has been raised through private donations to help with
preservation. Introducing the first lady to a crowd of more than 400 people,
Anna Roosevelt, granddaughter of Eleanor Roosevelt, said: ''The legacy of this
place is the legacy of a great woman who simply took stock of who she was and
where she was and then tried to be useful. Such a woman is Hillary Rodham
Clinton.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tiger Woods Leads U.S. Open
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Tiger Woods made history at the U.S. Open
Saturday with a six-stroke lead after 36 holes at Pebble Beach. Miguel Angel
Jimenez of Spain and Thomas Bjorn of Denmark, who started the third round six
strokes off the pace, quickly dropped out of sight.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rockies Rout Diamondbacks 14-5
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Jeffrey Hammonds hit two of Colorado's four home runs and
drove in four runs as the Colorado Rockies beat the Arizona Diamondbacks 14-5 on
Saturday night. The victory moved the Rockies within one game of first-place
Arizona in the NL West. It's the closest Colorado has been to the top spot this
late in the season since June 11, 1997.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA
</SUBHEAD>
